\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Comments on Minitwistors and the Celestial Supersphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Igor Mol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Affiliation
State University of Campinas (Unicamp)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author Email
igormol@ime.unicamp.br
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Continuing our program of deriving aspects of celestial holography from
 string theory, we extend the Roiban-Spradlin-Volovich-Witten (RSVW) formalism
 to celestial amplitudes.
 We reformulate the tree-level maximally-helicity-violating (MHV) celestial
 leaf amplitudes for gluons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 supersymmetric Yang-Mills (SYM) theory and for gravitons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity in terms of 
\emph on
minitwistor wavefunctions
\emph default
.
 These are defined as representatives of cohomology classes on the minitwistor
 space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

, associated to the three-dimensional Euclidean anti-de Sitter space.
 In this framework, celestial leaf amplitudes are expressed as integrals
 over the moduli space of minitwistor lines.
 We construct a minitwistor generating functional for MHV leaf amplitudes
 using the Quillen determinant line bundle, extending the approach originally
 developed by Boels, Mason and Skinner.
 Building on this formalism, we propose supersymmetric celestial conformal
 field theories (CFTs) as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-models, where the worldsheet is given by the celestial supersphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1|2}$
\end_inset

, and the target space is the minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

.
 We demonstrate that the semiclassical effective action of these 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-models reproduces the MHV gluonic and gravitational leaf amplitudes in
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity.
 This construction provides a concrete realisation of the supersymmetric
 celestial CFT framework recently introduced by Tropper (2024).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Tropper:2024evi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposed a general framework for constructing celestial CFTs that are expected
 to serve as holographic duals to spacetime 
\emph on
supersymmetric
\emph default
 field theories.
 In this paper, we provide a concrete realisation of Tropper's proposal
 by building supersymmetric celestial CFTs on the celestial 
\emph on
supersphere
\emph default
.
 These theories are formulated as sigma models, where the target space is
 the supersymmetric extension of minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

, associated with three-dimensional Euclidean anti-de Sitter space, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The models we construct are defined by an action functional that ensures
 a well-posed variational principle, allowing the use of the path-integral
 formalism to quantise these theories.
 We demonstrate that, in the semiclassical limit, these minitwistor celestial
 CFTs reproduce the tree-level maximally-helicity-violating (MHV) celestial
 leaf amplitudes for gluons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 supersymmetric Yang-Mills (SYM) theory and for gravitons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work builds on the observation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bu2023celestial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, who demonstrated that the Mellin transform defines a mapping between cohomolog
y classes in projective twistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{PT}$
\end_inset

 and minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 By applying both the Mellin and Penrose transforms, one establishes a correspon
dence where twistor wavefunctions are mapped to bulk-to-boundary propagators
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 Building on this, we introduce 
\emph on
minitwistor wavefunctions
\emph default
, which represent cohomology classes on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 and, through the Penrose transform, generate solutions to the covariant
 wave equation on 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 These wavefunctions satisfy an integral relation, which we refer to as
 the 
\emph on
celestial Roiban-Spradlin-Volovich-Witten 
\emph default
(RSVW) 
\emph on
identity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also propose a new interpretation of celestial leaf amplitudes.
 The standard approach involves foliating Klein space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{\left(2,2\right)}$
\end_inset

 into hyperbolic leaves and expressing physical scattering amplitudes as
 integrals over these leaves.
 In our reformulation, we introduce a different basis by expressing celestial
 amplitudes in terms of minitwistor wavefunctions.
 Using the celestial RSVW identity, we show that the leaf amplitudes for
 gluons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory and for gravitons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity can be written as integrals over the moduli space of minitwistor
 lines
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Minitwistor-Geometry"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for a definition.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we prove that these leaf amplitudes vanish if the gluon or graviton
 insertion points do not lie on a common minitwistor line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is also shown that minitwistor wavefunctions satisfy another integral
 relation, which we call the 
\emph on
celestial Boels-Mason-Skinner
\emph default
 
\emph on
identity
\emph default
.
 This property is derived from an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold application of the Penrose transform.
 Using this result, we construct a generating functional for MHV celestial
 amplitudes in terms of the Quillen determinant line bundle, which establishes
 a direct link between the celestial RSVW formalism and the semiclassical
 effective action of the minitwistor celestial CFTs developed in this work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Organisation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Minitwistor-Wavefunctions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we begin with a brief review of the Penrose integral-geometric transform
 on minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

, followed by the introduction of minitwistor wavefunctions.
 We then derive both the celestial RSVW identity and the Boels-Mason-Skinner
 identity.
 In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:-Supersymmetric-Yang-Mills"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we reformulate the tree-level MHV gluonic celestial leaf amplitudes in
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory using the celestial RSVW formalism and derive the corresponding
 minitwistor generating functional.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:-Supergravity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 extends these results to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity.
 In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Minitwistor-String-Theories"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we construct the minitwistor celestial CFTs in detail and show that the
 minitwistor generating functional arises as the semiclassical effective
 action obtained through the path-integral quantisation of our models.
 Finally, in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Discussion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we outline future directions of our research program aimed at deriving
 aspects of celestial holography from string theory.
\end_layout

