\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Physical Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main goal of this paper is to formulate a sigma model on the celestial
 
\emph on
supersphere
\emph default
, whose target space is the non-singular quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

, representing the 
\emph on
minitwistor space
\emph default
 associated with the three-dimensional hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 This model is designed to reproduce semiclassically the tree-level MHV
 celestial leaf amplitudes for gluons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory and for gravitons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key part of this construction is the introduction of 
\emph on
minitwistor wavefunctions
\emph default
, which are precisely defined in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Minitwistor-Wavefunctions-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 These wavefunctions serve as the basic building blocks for the vertex operators
 in the minitwistor sigma model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the recent work by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bu2023celestial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the 
\emph on
celestial leaf amplitudes 
\emph default
may be derived through an alternative, yet mathematically equivalent, formalism.
 The original aproach of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "casali2022celestial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "melton2024celestial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 involves foliating Klein space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{\left(2.2\right)}$
\end_inset

 by hyperbolic leaves and expressing physical scattering amplitudes as integrals
 over these leaves.
 In the alternative approach, one begins with twistor wavefunctions and
 subsequently performs a Mellin transform with respect to one of the spinor
 variables.
 This is followed by the application of the Penrose transform from minitwistor
 space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 to the hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

, thus recovering the bulk-to-boundary propagator 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\Delta}\left(X;z,\bar{z}\right)$
\end_inset

 for the covariant Laplacian 
\begin_inset Formula $\square_{H_{3}^{+}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minitwistor wavefunctions satisfy two important properties: the 
\emph on
celestial Boels-Mason-Skinner
\emph default
 (BMS) and 
\emph on
Roiban-Spradlin-Volovich-Witten
\emph default
 (RSVW) 
\emph on
integral identities
\emph default
.
 The BMS identities (discussed in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:BMS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) will be employed in the construction of a generating functional for the
 celestial leaf amplitudes.
 On the other hand, the RSVW identity (derived in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "RSVW"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) will be used in reformulating these amplitudes as a Fourier transform
 in minitwistor space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the next subsection, we review the extension of the Penrose integral-geometri
c transform to the minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Review: Minitwistor Penrose Transform and 
\begin_inset Formula $AdS_{3}$
\end_inset

 Wave Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Minitwistor-Penrose-Transform"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formalisation of the Penrose transform is naturally expressed through
 the language of integral geometry
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A general review of the subject is provided in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "guillemin1987perspectives"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For a rigorous textbook treatment, we direct the reader to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "helgason2011integral,helgason2022groups,helgason2024geometric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, the text by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "quinto2013geometric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provides an accessible account well-suited for those interested in physical
 applications.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The basic structure in this branch of geometric analysis is a 
\emph on
double fibration
\emph default
,
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}  
\backslash
label{diagram}  
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[row sep=large, column sep=large] & 
\backslash
mathscr{Z} 
\backslash
arrow[dl, "
\backslash
textstyle q_{1}"' ] 
\backslash
arrow[dr, "
\backslash
textstyle q_{2}"] & 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathscr{X} & & 
\backslash
mathscr{Y} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}  
\backslash
end{equation} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{X}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Z}$
\end_inset

 denote smooth manifolds, and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1},q_{2}$
\end_inset

 are fibre maps.
 The diagram (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "diagram"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) qualifies as a double fibration if the product map:
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation} 
\backslash
label{eq:-41} 
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[column sep=large] q_{1} 
\backslash
times q_{2} : 
\backslash
mathscr{Z} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
mathscr{X} 
\backslash
times 
\backslash
mathscr{Y} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

is an embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Z}$
\end_inset

 as a submanifold of the product space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{X}\times\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\times q_{2}$
\end_inset

 is indeed an embedding, it follows directly that, for any point 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

, the fibre 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(y\right)\coloneqq q_{2}^{-1}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 is smoothly embedded as a submanifold of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the double fibration (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "diagram"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) induces a family of submanifolds 
\begin_inset Formula $\{F\left(y\right)\}_{y\in\mathscr{Y}}$
\end_inset

, with each submanifold 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 smoothly embedded into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{X}$
\end_inset

 and parametrised by points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key idea of integral geometry is that geometric objects on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{X}$
\end_inset

 can be transported to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

 via the intermediate space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, given a differential form (or holomorphic section) 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{X}$
\end_inset

, the pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}^{*}\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 yields a corresponding form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\emph on
integral-geometric transform
\emph default
 is then constructed by integrating the pullback over the fibres of the
 map 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

, resulting in a function or section on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 Formally, the integral-geometric transform is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a\mapsto\widetilde{a}\left(y\right)\coloneqq\underset{q_{2}^{-1}\left(y\right)}{\int}\,q_{1}^{*}\left(a\right),\label{eq:-43}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{a}$
\end_inset

 denotes the resulting form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important feature of this integral transform is that, whenever the pullback
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}^{*}\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 remains constant along the fibres of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

, the transformed form 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{a}$
\end_inset

 must satisfy certain differential equations on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 This observation formalises a result originally noted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bateman1918solution"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and rediscovered by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "penrose1969solutions"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Minitwistor Geometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Minitwistor-Geometry"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we provide a concise discussion of how the hyperbolic geometry of the
 three-dimensional real manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

 can be realised within the projective geometry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

, subject to appropriate reality conditions.
 Additionally, we give a brief but mathematically rigorous introduction
 to the minitwistor space
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jones1984minitwistors,jones1985minitwistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hitchin1982monopoles,hitchin1982twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "honda2011minitwistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 associated to the hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, we proceed to specialise the abstract framework of integral geometry,
 as delineated above, to the geometry of minitwistor space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 denote the complexification of the real hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

, and introduce the complexified projective spinor bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{PS}_{3}\coloneqq\mathbf{CP}^{3}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 as the trivial bundle whose base space is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

 and the typical fibre consists of the projectivised space of (undotted)
 two-component spinors.
 The relevant double fibration in this geometric setup is given by the diagram:
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[row sep=large, column sep=large] & 
\backslash
mathbf{PS}_{3} 
\backslash
arrow[dl, "
\backslash
displaystyle
\backslash
widetilde{q}_{1}"'] 
\backslash
arrow[dr, "
\backslash
displaystyle
\backslash
widetilde{q}_{2}"] & 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbf{MT} & & 
\backslash
mathbf{H}_{3} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The first bundle map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{q}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is defined via the minitwistor incidence relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{q}_{1}:\,\left(X_{A\dot{A}}\,,\,\lambda^{A}\right)\,\mapsto\,\left(\lambda^{A},\,\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 represents homogeneous coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 denotes homogeneous spinor coordinates in the fibre 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The second bundle map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{q}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the trivial surjection 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{q}_{2}:(X_{A\dot{A}},\lambda^{A})\mapsto X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having established the double fibration structure, it remains to specify
 the module of sections of the holomorphic vector bundle on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 upon which the integral-geometric transform defined in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-43"

\end_inset

) operates.
 Therefore, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}_{p,q}^{\infty}\left(\mathbf{MT}\right)$
\end_inset

 denote the space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 complex-valued functions 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{C}^{*}\right)^{2}\times\left(\mathbf{C}^{*}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the following homogeneity property:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h\left(a\cdot\lambda^{A},b\cdot\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)=a^{p}b^{q}\,\,\,h\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for every pair of nonzero complex scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 In Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-Holomorphic-Vector"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we prove that the function space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}_{p,q}^{\infty}\left(\mathbf{MT}\right)$
\end_inset

 is canonically identified with the module 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{\infty}(\mathcal{O}(p,q))$
\end_inset

 of smooth sections on the holomorphic vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(p,q\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Scalar Representatives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In four-dimensional physics, twistor theory
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a modern introduction, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "adamo2017lectures,atiyah2017twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Appendix A"
key "witten2004perturbative"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 characterises solutions to (linearised) massless field equations on spacetime
 through equivalence classes in the cohomology group of projective twistor
 space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{PT}$
\end_inset

, associated with the module of sections of the holomorphic vector bundle
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(p\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{PT}$
\end_inset

.
 We now extend this framework to the setting of 
\begin_inset Formula $AdS_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A similar discussion for the 
\begin_inset Formula $AdS_{5}$
\end_inset

 case can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "adamo2016twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To explain this construction, we restrict our attention to the case of
 scalar representatives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[\mathsf{f}]\in H^{0,1}\left(\mathbf{MT},\mathcal{O}\left(-2,-\Delta\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}\in\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 be a point on the complexified hyperboloid embedded in projective space,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}\subset\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 denotes homogeneous coordinates.
 Define the rational curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 as the line of incidence in minitwistor space:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)=\left\{ \left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)\in\mathbf{MT}\,\big|\,\mu_{\dot{A}}=\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}}\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Employing the sheaf-theoretic notation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "forster1981compact"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}$
\end_inset

 denote the restriction homomorphism to the incidence line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

, defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}(g)\left(\lambda^{A}\right)\coloneqq g\left(\lambda^{A},\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}}\right),\,\,\,\forall\,[g]\in H^{0,1}\left(\mathbf{MT},\mathcal{O}\left(-2,-\Delta\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us restrict our attention to a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 valued in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(-2,-\Delta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The Penrose transform can be introduced as a mapping from representatives
 of the cohomology class 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{0,1}\left(\mathbf{MT},\mathcal{O}\left(-2,-\Delta\right)\right)$
\end_inset

, given by the Penrose integral:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{f}\mapsto\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}{\int}\left\langle \lambda d\lambda\right\rangle \,\,\,\rho_{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}\big(\mathsf{f}\big)\left(\lambda\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus, define:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{\Delta}\left(X\right)\coloneqq\left|X\right|^{\Delta}\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}{\int}\left\langle \lambda d\lambda\right\rangle \,\,\,\rho_{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}\big(\mathsf{f}\big)\left(\lambda\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Accordingly, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\Delta}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 is invariant under the flow of the Euler vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\Upsilon$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{£}_{\Upsilon}F_{\Delta}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\Delta}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree zero and, therefore, yields a well-defined 
\emph on
function
\emph default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To verify the consistency of this construction, note that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial X}\cdot\frac{\partial}{\partial X}\left(\frac{F_{\Delta}\left(X\right)}{\left|X\right|^{\Delta}}\right)=0\iff\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}\,\mathsf{f}=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since every 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{f}$
\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\partial}$
\end_inset

-exact integrates to zero, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\Delta}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 is determined by the cohomology class 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathsf{f}]$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{0,1}\left(\mathbf{MT},\mathcal{O}\left(-2,-\Delta\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, from the invariance of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\Delta}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 under the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Upsilon$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X^{A\dot{A}}\frac{\partial}{\partial X^{A\dot{A}}}F_{\Delta}\left(X\right)=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we deduce that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon^{AB}\varepsilon^{\dot{A}\dot{B}}\frac{\partial}{\partial X^{A\dot{A}}}\frac{\partial}{\partial X^{B\dot{B}}}\left(\frac{F_{\Delta}\left(X\right)}{\left|X\right|^{\Delta}}\right)=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is equivalent to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\square_{\mathbf{H}_{3}}\,F_{\Delta}\left(X\right)=\Delta\left(\Delta+2\right)F_{\Delta}\left(X\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude that the Penrose transform establishes a correspondence between
 cohomology classes of the non-singular quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 associated to the holomorphic vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(-2,-\Delta\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

, and conformal primaries of the minisuperspace limit of the 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

-WZNW model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minitwistor Wavefunctions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Minitwistor-Wavefunctions-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now prepared to introduce the notion of a minitwistor wavefunction.
 This object shows an interesting connection between the Mellin and Penrose
 transforms.
 It will be demonstrated that the Mellin transform induces a mapping between
 cohomology classes on projective twistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{PT}$
\end_inset

, and corresponding cohomology classes on the nonsingular quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 By subsequently applying the Penrose transform, it will become clear that
 twistor wavefunctions are mapped to bulk-to-boundary Green's functions
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "teschner1997conformal,teschner1999mini,teschner1999structure,teschner2000operator,ribault2005h3+"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for the covariant Laplacian 
\begin_inset Formula $\square_{H_{3}^{+}}$
\end_inset

 on the hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset


\emph on
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation*
From now on, we shall adopt a simplified notational convention for spinor
 functions.
 The explicit display of abstract spinor indices in the arguments of such
 functions will be reserved exclusively for their initial definition.
 Thereafter, the spinor type (dotted 
\emph on
vs.

\emph default
 undotted) comprising the domain of each function will remain implicit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Twistor Scalar Wavefunction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider the twistor scalar wavefunction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{f}_{w}\in\Omega^{0,1}\left(\mathbf{PT},\mathcal{O}\left(-w\right)\right),\label{eq:-41}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which admits the following integral representation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{f}_{w}\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}};\text{m}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{C}^{*}}{\int}\,\frac{dt}{t}\,t^{w}\,\,\,\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(z^{A}-t\lambda^{A}\big)\,\exp\left(i\,t\left[\mu\bar{z}\right]\right).\label{eq:-13}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the above expression, the spinor delta function is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}^{2}\left(\lambda^{A}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\frac{1}{\left(2\pi i\right)^{2}}\,\bigwedge_{A\in\{1,2\}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\left(\frac{1}{\lambda^{A}}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The ordered pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{m}\coloneqq\left(z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes the collection of quantum numbers characterising the state of the
 particle associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{f}_{w}$
\end_inset

.
 For the massless gauge bosons participating in the scattering processes
 to be considered in the subsequent sections, the spinors are chosen be
 to normalised as 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{A}=\left(z,1\right)^{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}=\left(1,-\bar{z}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z,\bar{z}\right)$
\end_inset

 parametrises the insertion points on the celestial sphere.
 In what follows, we shall omit the explicit dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 from the arguments of any wavefunctions to streamline the notation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The structure of the affine integral (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-13"

\end_inset

) implies that the twistor scalar wavefunction satisfies the homogeneity
 property:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{f}_{w}\left(a\lambda,a\mu\right)=a^{-w}\mathsf{f}_{w}\left(\lambda,\mu\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbf{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

, as expected from the corresponding cohomology class (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-41"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Performing the affine integral in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-13"

\end_inset

) yields the explicit form of the twistor scalar wavefunction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{f}_{w}\left(\lambda,\mu\right)\,=\,\overline{\delta}\left(\left\langle \lambda z\right\rangle \right)\,\left(\frac{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }\right)^{1-w}\exp\left(i\frac{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }\left[\mu\bar{z}\right]\right).\label{eq:-42}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now define the 
\emph on
minitwistor wavefunction
\emph default
 with 
\emph on
celestial conformal weight 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 as the Mellin transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{f}_{w}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the dotted spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathsf{f}}_{\Delta,w}\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{R}_{+}^{\times}}{\int}\,\frac{ds}{s}\,s^{\Delta}\,\,\,\mathsf{f}_{w}\left(\lambda^{A},s\mu_{\dot{A}}\right),\label{eq:-44}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}_{+}^{\times}\coloneqq\left(\mathbf{R}_{+},\times\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes the multiplicative group of positive real numbers, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{ds}{s}$
\end_inset

 is the associated Haar measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-13"

\end_inset

) into Definition (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-44"

\end_inset

), we obtain the complete integral representation of the minitwistor wavefunctio
n:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathsf{f}}_{\Delta,w}\left(\lambda,\mu\right)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{R}_{+}^{\times}}{\int}\,\frac{ds}{s}\,s^{\Delta}\,\underset{\mathbf{C}^{*}}{\int}\,\frac{dt}{t}\,t^{w}\,\,\,\overline{\delta}^{2}\big(z^{A}-t\lambda^{A}\big)\,\exp\left(i\,st\left[\mu\bar{z}\right]\right).\label{eq:-16}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The structure of the Mellin and affine integrals in the above expression
 reveals that the minitwistor wavefunction exhibits the homogeneity property:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathsf{f}}_{\Delta,w}\left(a\lambda,b\mu\right)\,=\,a^{\Delta-w}b^{-\Delta}\,\,\,\widehat{\mathsf{f}}_{\Delta,w}\left(\lambda,\mu\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbf{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mathsf{f}}_{\Delta,w}\in\Omega^{0,1}\left(\mathbf{MT},\mathcal{O}\left(\Delta-w,-\Delta\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Finally, performing the integrals in the expression (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-16"

\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{f}_{\Delta,w}$
\end_inset

, we derive the explicit form of the minitwistor scalar wavefunction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathsf{f}}_{\Delta,w}\left(\lambda,\mu\right)\,=\,\overline{\delta}\left(\left\langle \lambda z\right\rangle \right)\,\left(\frac{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }\right)^{1+\Delta-w}\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)}{\left[\mu\bar{z}\right]^{\Delta}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Celestial Boels-Mason-Skinner Integral Identity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:BMS"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection, we derive an integral identity that will serve as a
 key step in constructing the generating functional for celestial leaf amplitude
s, analogous to the twistor-space generating functional introduced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "boels2007twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This identity will henceforth be referred to as the 
\emph on
celestial Boels-Mason-Skinner 
\emph default
(BMS) 
\emph on
identity
\emph default

\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There should be no confusion with the BMS group, as each applies to a different
 physical context.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph on
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by considering a distinguished representative of minitwistor scalar
 wavefunctions, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}_{\Delta}\in\Omega^{0,1}\left(\mathbf{MT},\mathcal{O}\left(0,-\Delta\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

defined by the expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}_{\Delta}\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\widehat{\mathsf{f}}_{\Delta,\Delta}\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right),\label{eq:-22}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and taking the explicit form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}_{\Delta}\left(\lambda,\mu\right)\,=\,\overline{\delta}\left(\left\langle \lambda z\right\rangle \right)\,\frac{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }\,\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)}{\left[\mu\bar{z}\right]^{\Delta}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Penrose transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 is computed by restricting this wavefunction to a specific holomorphic
 curve in minitwistor space.
 Let the minitwistor line corresponding to the ``spacetime'' point 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 be defined by the locus of incidence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)\,\coloneqq\,\big\{\,\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\big)\,\in\mathbf{MT}\,\big|\,\mu_{\dot{A}}=\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}}\big\}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Following the sheaf-theoretic notation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "forster1981compact"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the restriction homomorphism to the conic 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{X}$
\end_inset

, which acts on cohomology representatives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[g]\in H^{0,1}\left(\mathbf{MT},\mathcal{O}\left(0,-\Delta\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

according to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{X}\left(g\right)\left(\lambda\right)\,\coloneqq\,g\left(\lambda^{A},\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 denote the canonical projection of the conic onto the projective line.
 We introduce a trivialisation of the fibration 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 by a choice of homogeneous coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The natural orientation of the fibre is induced by the volume form 
\begin_inset Formula $D\lambda\coloneqq\varepsilon_{AB}\lambda^{A}d\lambda^{B}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{A}$
\end_inset

 be a pair of constant two-component spinors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, the Penrose transform of: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mathcal{F}_{\Delta}\left(\lambda,\mu;z,\bar{z}\right)}{\left\langle a\lambda\right\rangle \left\langle \lambda b\right\rangle },
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is given by the integral-geometric transform:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mathcal{F}_{\Delta}\left(\lambda,\mu;z,\bar{z}\right)}{\left\langle a\lambda\right\rangle \left\langle \lambda b\right\rangle }\,\mapsto\,\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}{\int}\,D\lambda\,\,\,\rho_{X}\left(\mathcal{F}_{\Delta}\right)\left(\lambda\right)\,\,\,\frac{1}{\left\langle a\lambda\right\rangle \left\langle \lambda b\right\rangle },
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which, upon evaluation, yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|X\right|^{\Delta}\,\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}{\int}\,D\lambda\,\,\,\rho_{X}\left(\mathcal{F}_{\Delta}\right)\left(\lambda\right)\,\frac{1}{\left\langle a\lambda\right\rangle \left\langle \lambda b\right\rangle }\,=\,\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)\,\frac{\left|X\right|^{\Delta}}{\langle z|X|\bar{z}]^{\Delta}}\,=\,\frac{K_{\Delta}\left(X;z,\bar{z}\right)}{\left\langle a\lambda\right\rangle \left\langle \lambda b\right\rangle },
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\Delta}\left(X;z,\bar{z}\right)$
\end_inset

 is identified with the bulk-to-boundary propagator
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gelfandgeneralized"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "teschner1997conformal,teschner1999mini,teschner1999structure,teschner2000operator"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "costa2014spinning"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "penedones2017tasi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 on the hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\Delta\right)\coloneqq i^{\Delta}\Gamma\left(\Delta\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now proceed by employing an inductive argument over 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

 to generalise this result to an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold product of Penrose transforms.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z,\bar{z}\right)$
\end_inset

 label boundary points of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold Penrose transform gives the celestial BMS identity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)^{\times n}}{\int}\,\bigwedge_{i=1}^{n}\,D\lambda_{i}\,\,\,\left|X\right|^{\Delta_{i}}\rho_{X}\left(\mathcal{F}_{\Delta}\right)\left(\lambda\right)\frac{1}{\lambda_{i}\cdot\lambda_{i+1}}=\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{K_{\Delta}\left(X;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.\label{eq:-18}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Celestial Roiban-Spradlin-Volovich-Witten Integral Identity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "RSVW"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now proceed to establish that the restriction homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{X}$
\end_inset

, associated with a minitwistor line associated to a ``spacetime'' point
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

, may be enforced by means of a 
\emph on
weighted
\emph default
 Dirac delta function on minitwistor space.
 This will allow us to derive an identity analogous to Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-18"

\end_inset

), expressed as an integral over the minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theory of distributions was extended to include sections of differential
 forms by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "de2012differentiable"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, building on earlier work by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "schwartz1954espaces,schwartz1957theorie,schwartz1958theorie"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this framework, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 denote a distributional form valued in the holomorphic vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\Delta-2,-2\right)$
\end_inset

, defined by the expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\left(\mu_{\dot{A}},\pi_{\dot{A}}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\frac{1}{\left(2\pi i\right)^{2}}\,\underset{\mathbf{C}^{*}}{\int}\,\frac{dt}{t}\,t^{\Delta}\,\bigwedge_{\dot{A}\in\{\dot{1},\dot{2}\}}\overline{\partial}\,\left(\frac{1}{\mu_{\dot{A}}-t\pi_{\dot{A}}}\right),\label{eq:-40}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which imposes the projective coincidence condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\dot{A}}\sim\pi_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 in the complex projective line.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To perform the affine integration over 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, we invoke the analytic continuation of the Dirac delta function, given
 by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}\left(z\right)\,\coloneqq\,\frac{1}{2\pi i}\,\overline{\partial}\,z^{-1}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Applying this definition to the integrand of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-40"

\end_inset

), we derive the following explicit form for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\left(\mu,\pi\right)\,=\,\overline{\delta}\left([\mu\pi]\right)\,\left(\frac{[\mu\bar{\iota}]}{[\pi\bar{\iota}]}\right)^{\Delta-1},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\iota}^{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 denotes a fixed reference spinor that is arbitrarily chosen but non-vanishing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now introduce a representative wavefunction on minitwistor space,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{\Delta}\in\Omega^{0,1}\left(\mathbf{MT},\mathcal{O}\left(\Delta,-\Delta\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

defined by the expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{\Delta}\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\widehat{\mathsf{f}}_{\Delta,0}\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and taking the explicit form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{\Delta}\left(\lambda,\mu\right)\,=\,\overline{\delta}\left(\left\langle \lambda z\right\rangle \right)\,\left(\frac{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }\right)^{1+\Delta}\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)}{\left[\mu\bar{z}\right]^{\Delta}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}\in\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

, we define the following distribution on minitwistor space:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{\Delta}\left(X_{A\dot{A}};\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta}\left(\mu_{\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}\right)\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{\Delta}\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)\frac{1}{\left\langle a\lambda\right\rangle \left\langle \lambda b\right\rangle },
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which takes values in the holomorphic vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(-2,-2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This definition enables us to write the following integral over minitwistor
 space:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{MT}}{\int}D\lambda\wedge D\mu\,\,\,g_{\Delta}\left(X;\lambda,\mu\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D\lambda\wedge D\mu$
\end_inset

 denotes the canonical volume form on the non-singular quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

, ensuring that the integral is projectively well-defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Utilising the explicit expressions derived above, we obtain the following
 form for 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\Delta}\left(X;\lambda,\mu\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{\Delta}\left(X;\lambda,\mu\right)=\overline{\delta}\left(\left\langle \lambda z\right\rangle \right)\overline{\delta}\left(\frac{\langle\lambda|X|\mu]}{\left|X\right|}\right)\left(\frac{\left\langle \lambda\iota\right\rangle }{\left\langle z\iota\right\rangle }\right)^{1+\Delta}\left(\frac{1}{[\mu\bar{\iota}]}\frac{\langle\lambda|X|\bar{\iota}]}{\left|X\right|}\right)^{1-\Delta}\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)}{\left[\mu\bar{z}\right]^{\Delta}}\,\,\,\frac{1}{\left\langle a\lambda\right\rangle \left\langle \lambda b\right\rangle }.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Introducing projective coordinates on minitwistor space via 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}^{I}\coloneqq\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)$
\end_inset

, and denoting the canonical volume form by 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{2}\mathsf{Z}=D\lambda\wedge D\mu$
\end_inset

, direct evaluation of the integral yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{MT}}{\int}D^{2}\mathsf{Z}\,\,\,g_{\Delta}\left(X;\lambda,\mu\right)=\frac{K_{\Delta}\left(X;z,\bar{z}\right)}{\left\langle a\lambda\right\rangle \left\langle \lambda b\right\rangle },
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is identified with the bulk-to-boundary propagator on 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, by applying an inductive argument on 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

, we derive the 
\emph on
celestial Roiban-Spradlin-Volovich-Witten 
\emph default
(RSVW) 
\emph on
identity
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\prod_{i=1}^{n}\underset{\mathbf{MT}}{\int}D^{2}\mathsf{Z}_{i}\,\,\,\overline{\delta}_{\Delta_{i}}\left(\mu_{i\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}\right)\,\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{\Delta_{i}}\left(\lambda_{i},\mu_{i};z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\frac{1}{\lambda_{i}\cdot\lambda_{i+1}}=\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{K_{\Delta_{i}}\left(X;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.\label{eq:-49}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the subsequent section, we shall employ this identity to reformulate
 the celestial leaf amplitudes for gluons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory, and subsequently extend the analysis to gravitons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 Supersymmetric Yang-Mills
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:-Supersymmetric-Yang-Mills"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The starting point of our analysis is the Parke-Taylor formula
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First introduced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "parke1986amplitude"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and subsequently provided with a rigorous derivation by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "berends1988recursive"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kim1997recursion"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For modern introductions, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elvang2013scattering,badger2024scattering"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Consider a scattering process in four-dimensional Yang-Mills theory involving
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 gluons in the MHV configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{-},2^{-},3^{+},...,n^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding scattering amplitude, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}$
\end_inset

, is expressed as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{A}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},s_{i}\right)\,=\,ig^{n-2}\,\delta^{\left(4\right)}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}s_{i}q^{\mu}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\right)\,\left\langle \nu_{1}\nu_{2}\right\rangle ^{4}\,\mathsf{Tr}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{\mathsf{T}^{a_{i}}}{\nu_{i}\cdot\nu_{i+1}}.\label{eq:-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 denotes the Yang-Mills coupling constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},...,a_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the colour indices associated with the external gluons, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{T}^{a}$
\end_inset

 are the generators of the gauge group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

.
 These generators satisfy the normalisation condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Tr}(\mathsf{T}^{a}\mathsf{T}^{b})=\frac{1}{2}\boldsymbol{k}^{ab}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}^{ab}$
\end_inset

 denotes the Cartan-Killing form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

, as well as the Lie algebra commutation relations 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathsf{T}^{a},\mathsf{T}^{b}]=if^{abc}\mathsf{T}^{c}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{abc}$
\end_inset

 are the structure constants of the Lie algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}\simeq(T_{e}(\mathbf{G}),[\cdot,\cdot])$
\end_inset

.
 We also adopt the convention 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{n+1}^{A}\coloneqq\nu_{1}^{A}$
\end_inset

, which ensures cyclic symmetry in the denominator of the Parke-Taylor formula.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To proceed, we reformulate the amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},s_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 in terms of the frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the normalised spinor basis 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}^{A}\coloneqq\left(1,z_{i}\right)^{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{z}_{i\dot{A}}\coloneqq\left(-\bar{z}_{i},1\right)$
\end_inset

, utilising Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-1"

\end_inset

) along with the integral representation of the four-dimensional delta-function,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta^{\left(4\right)}\left(p\right)=\frac{1}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{4}}{\int}d^{4}x\,\,\,e^{ip\cdot x},\,\,\,\forall\,p^{\mu}\in\mathbf{R}^{4}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This yields the expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{A}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},s_{i}\right)\,=\,\frac{ig^{n-2}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{4}}{\int}d^{4}x\,\,\,\mathsf{Tr}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,s_{i}^{e_{i}}\,\exp\left(i\,s_{i}\,\langle z_{i}|x|\bar{z}_{i}]\right)\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{a_{i}}}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.\label{eq:-48}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Grassmann-valued Spinors; Berezin-de Witt Integral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transition to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory is achieved via the on-shell superfield formalism
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We follow the techniques developed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "grisaru1977some"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "brink1977supersymmetric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferber1977supertwistors"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, as reviewed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wess2020supersymmetry"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elvang2013scattering"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 To this end, we introduce Grassmann-valued two-component spinors 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{A}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\alpha\leq4$
\end_inset

 indexes the supersymmetry generators.
 These variables satisfy the normalisation condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\int d^{0|2}\theta\,\,\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\theta_{B}^{\alpha}=\varepsilon_{AB},$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{0|2}\theta$
\end_inset

 denotes the Berezin-de Witt integration measure
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Introduced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "berezin2013introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dewitt1992supermanifolds"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For a modern and rigorous mathematical exposition, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "manin1997introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 over the fermionic variables.
 Then, defining the Grassmann-valued coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{i}^{\alpha}\coloneqq z_{i}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, we note the identity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(z_{i}\cdot z_{j})^{4}=\int d^{0|8}\theta\,\,\,\prod_{\alpha=1}^{4}\,\xi_{i}^{\alpha}\xi_{j}^{\alpha},\,\,\,\text{for all}\,1\leq i,j\leq n.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, we must specify both the integration measure and the domain
 over which the super-amplitudes are defined.
 Thus, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{4|8}$
\end_inset

 denote the supersymmetric extension of real four-dimensional Euclidean
 space, augmented with the Grassmann-valued coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{A}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a=1,...,8\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The Berezin-de Witt integration measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{4|8}$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{4|8}x\coloneqq d^{4}x\wedge d^{0|8}\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, the amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}$
\end_inset

 obtained in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-48"

\end_inset

) can be reformulated as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{A}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},s_{i}\right)\,=\,\frac{ig^{n-2}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{4|8}}{\int}d^{4|8}x\,\prod_{\alpha=1}^{4}\,\xi_{1}^{\alpha}\xi_{2}^{\alpha}\,\,\,\mathsf{Tr}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,s_{i}^{e_{i}}\,\exp\left(i\,s_{i}\,\langle z_{i}|x|\bar{z}_{i}]\right)\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{a_{i}}}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM Super-amplitude
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To extend this to 
\emph on
supersymmetric 
\emph default
amplitudes, we define the superfield encoding the particle spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi\left(\xi^{\alpha}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\mathsf{a}^{-}+\xi^{\alpha}\,\lambda_{\alpha}+\frac{1}{2!}\,\xi^{\alpha}\xi^{\beta}\,\,\,\phi_{\alpha\beta}+\frac{1}{3!}\,\xi^{\alpha}\xi^{\beta}\xi^{\gamma}\varepsilon_{\alpha\beta\gamma\delta}\,\,\,\eta^{\delta}+\mathsf{a}^{+}\,\prod_{\alpha=1}^{4}\xi^{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{a}_{i}^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 represent the classical expectation values associated with the annihilation
 operators for gluons of positive and negative helicities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, the gluonic super-amplitude in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory can be expressed as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathscr{A}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},s_{i}\right)=\frac{ig^{n-2}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{4|8}}{\int}d^{4|8}x\,\,\,\mathsf{Tr}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,s_{i}^{e_{i}}\,\varphi\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)\,\exp\left(i\,s_{i}\,\langle z_{i}|x|\bar{z}_{i}]\right)\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{a_{i}}}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.\label{eq:-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minitwistor Amplitudes for Gluons
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now positioned to derive the main result of this section.
 We shall demonstrate that the celestial leaf amplitude for gluons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory admits a representation as an integral over the moduli space
 of minitwistor lines in the non-singular quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mellin Transform and Leaf Amplitudes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by recalling the definition of the celestial amplitude
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cf.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "pasterski2017conformal,pasterski2017gluon,pasterski2017flat,arkani2021celestial,banerjee2020modified,banerjee2021mhv"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For recent pedagogical reviews, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "pasterski2021lectures,raclariu2021lectures,strominger2018lectures,aneesh2022celestial,pasterski2023chapter"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

-regulated Mellin transform:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathscr{A}}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\,\,\,\coloneqq\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\,\,\underset{\mathbf{R}_{+}^{\times}}{\int}\,\,\,\frac{ds_{i}}{s_{i}}\,s_{i}^{\Delta i}\,e^{-\varepsilon s_{i}}\,\,\,\mathscr{A}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},s_{i}\right),\label{eq:-12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}_{\times}^{+}\coloneqq(\mathbf{R}^{+},\cdot)$
\end_inset

 denotes the multiplicative group of positive real numbers, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{ds_{i}}{s_{i}}$
\end_inset

 the Haar measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}_{\times}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the expression for the gluon super-amplitude, obtained in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-2"

\end_inset

), into Definition (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-12"

\end_inset

) yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathscr{A}}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\,=\,\frac{ig^{n-2}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\,\,\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{4|8}}{\int}d^{4|8}x\,\,\,\mathsf{Tr}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{2h_{i}}\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)\,\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(x;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{a_{i}}}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.\label{eq:-14}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\Delta}\left(x;z,\bar{z}\right)$
\end_inset

 represents the celestial wavefunction
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "pasterski2017conformal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and our Appendix A.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for massless scalars, which is defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{\Delta}\left(x;z,\bar{z}\right)\coloneqq\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)}{\left(i\varepsilon+\langle z|x|\bar{z}]\right)^{\Delta}},\,\,\,\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)\coloneqq i^{-\Delta}\Gamma\left(\Delta\right).\label{eq:-46}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Additionally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{\Delta}\left(\xi\right)$
\end_inset

 is the superfield expansion for the Mellin-transformed mode coefficients:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{\Delta}\left(\xi^{\alpha}\right)\,=\,\widehat{\mathsf{a}}_{\Delta}^{-}\,+\,\xi^{\alpha}\,\widehat{\lambda}_{\Delta,\alpha}+\frac{1}{2!}\,\xi^{\alpha}\xi^{\beta}\,\,\,\widehat{\phi}_{\Delta,\alpha\beta}\,+\,\frac{1}{3!}\,\xi^{\alpha}\xi^{\beta}\xi^{\gamma}\,\varepsilon_{\alpha\beta\gamma\delta}\,\,\,\widehat{\eta}_{\Delta}^{\delta}\,+\,\widehat{\mathsf{a}}_{\Delta}^{+}\,\,\,\prod_{\alpha=1}^{4}\xi^{\alpha}.\label{eq:-52}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We note that the mode functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathsf{a}}_{\Delta}^{\pm}=\widehat{\mathsf{a}}_{\Delta}^{\pm}\left(z,\bar{z}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\lambda}_{\Delta,\alpha}=\widehat{\lambda}_{\Delta,\alpha}\left(z,\bar{z}\right)$
\end_inset

 etc.
 depends on the normalised spinor basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z_{i}^{A},\bar{z}_{i\dot{A}}\}$
\end_inset

, parametrising the insertion points of the gluons on the celestial sphere,
 and the conformal weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Leaf Representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now proceed to implement the formalism of celestial leaf amplitudes
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Leaf-Amplitudes-Review"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "melton2023celestial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, requiring a specification of both the integration measure and the domains
 over which the gluonic amplitudes will be constructed.
 To that end, we recall that, within the embedding-space formalism, spacetime
 points are parametrised by homogeneous coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

, where the real three-dimensional Euclidean hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

 is realised as the projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The geometry of the latter is given by the projectively invariant line-element
 
\begin_inset Formula $ds^{2}=\boldsymbol{g}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}dX^{A\dot{A}}\otimes dX^{B\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

, as defined in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-21"

\end_inset

).
 The orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is induced by the natural volume form
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gelfandgeneralized,gel_fand2003selected"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{3}X\coloneqq\varepsilon_{A\dot{A}}\,\varepsilon_{B\dot{B}}\,\varepsilon_{C\dot{C}}\,\varepsilon_{D\dot{D}}\,\,\,X^{A\dot{A}}\,dX^{B\dot{B}}\wedge dX^{C\dot{C}}\wedge dX^{D\dot{D}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extending this construction to the supersymmetric case requires promoting
 the bosonic coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 to their supersymmetric counterparts 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{X}^{\hat{I}}\coloneqq(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{A}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\leq\alpha\leq4\right)$
\end_inset

 are Grassmann-valued spinorial coordinates parametrising the ``fermionic
 dimensions.'' The corresponding Berezin-de Witt integration measure on the
 projective superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}$
\end_inset

 is then given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{3|8}\mathbb{X}\,\coloneqq\,\frac{D^{3}X}{\left|X\right|^{4}}\,\wedge\,d^{0|8}\theta.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With these preliminaries established, the celestial superamplitude in the
 leaf representation takes the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathscr{A}}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)=\frac{ig^{n-2}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{3}}\,\delta\left(\beta\right)\,\times\,A_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)+\big(\bar{z}_{i}\rightarrow-\bar{z}_{i}\big),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\coloneqq4-2\sum_{i=1}^{n}h_{i}$
\end_inset

 enforces the scaling constraint, and the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bar{z}_{i}\rightarrow-\bar{z}_{i})$
\end_inset

 signifies the repetition of the first term under the implied replacement.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 represents the gluonic leaf super-amplitude, which is defined as the following
 supersymmetric integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\,=\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}}{\int}D^{3|8}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\mathsf{Tr}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\boldsymbol{\varphi}\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)\,K_{2h_{i}}\left(X;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{a_{i}}}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.\label{eq:-10}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\Delta}\left(X;z,\bar{z}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the bulk-to-boundary Green's function for the covariant Laplacian 
\begin_inset Formula $\square_{\mathbf{H}_{3}}$
\end_inset

 with conformal weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, given in homogeneous coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}\in\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{\Delta}\left(X;z,\bar{z}\right)=\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)\frac{\left|X\right|^{\Delta}}{\langle z|X|\bar{z}]^{\Delta}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a concise review of leaf amplitudes, we refer the reader to Appendix
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Leaf-Amplitudes-Review"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For further mathematical details, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gelfandgeneralized"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "teschner1999mini"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "costa2014spinning,penedones2017tasi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Celestial RSVW Formalism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we reformulate Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-10"

\end_inset

) to derive the 
\emph on
celestial RSVW amplitude
\emph default
.
 First, the procedure requires the resolution of the identity for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 superfield 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varphi}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\varphi}\left(z_{r}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)=\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{0|4}}{\int}d^{0|4}\xi_{r}\,\,\,\delta^{\left(4\right)}\left(\xi_{r}^{\alpha}-z_{r}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)\,\boldsymbol{\varphi}\left(\xi_{i}^{\alpha}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This identity allows us to recast the leaf amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\,=\prod_{r=1}^{n}\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{0|4}}{\int}d^{0|4}\xi_{r}\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}}{\int}D^{3|8}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\mathsf{Tr}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\delta^{\left(4\right)}\left(\xi_{i}^{\alpha}-z_{i}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)\,\boldsymbol{\varphi}\left(\xi_{i}^{\alpha}\right)\,K_{2h_{i}}\left(X;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{a_{i}}}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}\label{eq:-50}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our subsequent task is to define the integration measure over which the
 gluonic leaf amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 will be expressed as an integral transform.
 As will be explained in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Minitwistor-String-Theories"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the minitwistor superspace
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cf.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "samann2009mini"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

 may be identified with the trivial vector superbundle
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rogers2007supermanifolds"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}\simeq\mathbf{MT}\times\mathbf{CP}^{0|4}$
\end_inset

, where the base manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the bosonic minitwistor space, while the typical fibres
 are isomorphic to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded vector space spanned by the Grassmann-odd projective coordinates
 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1,...,4$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector superbundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

 admits a local trivialisation in terms of homogeneous coordinates:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{Z}^{I}\,\coloneqq\,\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\xi^{\alpha}\right)\in\mathbf{CP}^{1|0}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1|0}\times\mathbf{CP}^{0|4}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The natural orientation of the total space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

 is induced by the Berezin-de Witt volume superform, given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}\,\coloneqq\,D\lambda\,\wedge\,D\mu\,\wedge\,d^{0|4}\xi.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Incorporating the celestial RSVW identity established in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-49"

\end_inset

), the gluonic leaf amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 admis the following representation in terms of an integral transform over
 minitwistor superspace:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & A_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)=\prod_{r=1}^{n}\underset{\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}}{\int}D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}_{i}\,\,\,\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{2h_{i}}\left(\xi_{i}^{\alpha}\right)\,\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{2h_{i}}\left(\lambda_{i},\mu_{i};z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}}{\int}D^{3|8}\mathbb{X}\\
 & \mathsf{Tr}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\,\,\overline{\delta}_{2h_{i}}\left(\mu_{i\dot{A}},\lambda_{i}^{A}\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}\right)\,\delta^{\left(4\right)}\left(\xi_{i}^{\alpha}-\lambda_{i}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)\,\,\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{a_{i}}}{\lambda_{i}\cdot\lambda_{i+1}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the key insight of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "witten2004perturbative,edward2004parity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we identify from the preceding expression the 
\emph on
minitwistor gluon wavefunction 
\emph default
with 
\emph on
celestial conformal weight 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Phi_{\Delta}\left(\mathsf{Z}^{I};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{\Delta}\left(\xi^{\alpha}\right)\,\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{\Delta}\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We thus conclude that the leaf amplitude can be interpreted as a Fourier-transfo
rm over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\,=\,\underset{\left(\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}\right)^{\times n}}{\int}\,\bigwedge_{i=1}^{n}\,D^{2|4}\mathsf{Z}_{i}\,\,\,\Phi_{2h_{i}}\left(\mathsf{Z}_{i};z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\widetilde{A}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(\mathsf{Z}_{i}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the Fourier-transformed amplitude is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{A}_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(\mathsf{Z}_{i}^{I}\right)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}}{\int}\,D^{3|8}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\mathsf{Tr}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\overline{\delta}_{2h_{i}}\left(\mu_{i\dot{A}},\lambda_{i}^{A}\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}\right)\,\delta^{\left(4\right)}\left(\xi_{i}^{\alpha}-\lambda_{i}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)\,\,\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{a_{i}}}{\lambda_{i}\cdot\lambda_{i+1}}.\label{eq:-51}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally we can formulate an important geometrical and physical interpretation
 of the result obtained.
 The (bosonic) spinor delta-functions appearing in the integrand serve to
 localise the integration over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to the locus of incidence curves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

, which, as previously discussed, correspond to minitwistor lines.
 These incidence curves are precisely the conic curves in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 that are associated with a fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}\in\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 on the hyperboloid, through the incidence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\dot{A}}=\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\emph on
The gluonic leaf amplitudes are identically null in all instances wherein
 the insertion points of the gluons fail to lie on a curve satisfying the
 defining incidence relation of a minitwistor line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, the leaf amplitudes acquires an elegant geometrical interpretation.
 
\emph on
It can be viewed as an integral over the moduli space of minitwistor lines
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 within the supersymmetric, non-singular quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

.
 
\emph default
However, it must be stressed that this integral cannot be interpreted as
 an ordinary volume form over the moduli space owing to the scaling dimensions
 associated with the delta functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{2h_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 It would be interesting to find an interpretation for Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-51"

\end_inset

) in the formalism developed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "movshev2006berezinian"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "adamo2013moduli"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Generating Functional
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Generating-Functional"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The geometric reformulation of gluonic leaf amplitudes enables the construction
 of a generating functional by invoking the Quillen determinant line bundle
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Introduced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "quillen1985determinants"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and further developed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "biswas1999determinant,brylinski1999geometric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For a review emphasising physical applications, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "freed1987determinant"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the celestial BMS identity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we shall explain in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Minitwistor-String-Theories"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, to each point in projective superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{X}^{\hat{I}}=\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)\in\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}$
\end_inset

, there correspond a 
\emph on
minitwistor superline
\emph default
 embedded in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

, defined by the locus of incidence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)\,\coloneqq\,\left\{ \,\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\xi^{\alpha}\big)\in\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}\,\Big|\,\mu_{\dot{A}}=\lambda^{A}\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|},\,\xi^{\alpha}=\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\,\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In what follows, we shall adopt the conventional notation for the restriction
 homomorphism associated with cohomological classes on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, let:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[g]\in H^{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}^{2|4},\mathcal{O}\left(-2,-\Delta\right)\big),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

be a representative of the Dolbeault cohomology class.
 The restriction of any such representative to the supercurve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 will be denoted by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,\left(\lambda^{A}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\rho_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}(g)\left(\lambda^{A}\right)\,=\,g\left(\lambda^{A},\lambda^{A}\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|},\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We introduce the 
\emph on
minitwistor background potential 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset

 as a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

-form on the holomorphic vector superbundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(-2,-\Delta\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

, taking values in the Lie algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 associated with the gauge group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Formally, this background potential is an element of the space:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\omega}\in\mathfrak{g}\otimes\Omega^{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}^{2|4},\mathcal{O}\left(-2,-\Delta\right)\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Our objective is now to demonstrate that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\digamma\left[\boldsymbol{\omega}\right]\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}}{\int}D^{3|8}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\log\det\left(\overline{\partial}\,+\boldsymbol{\omega}\right)\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

serves as a 
\emph on
generating functional 
\emph default
for the gluonic leaf amplitudes 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

, when evaluated at the specific background configuration:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{\omega}\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\xi^{\alpha};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\right)\,=\,\mathsf{T}^{a}\underset{\mathcal{P}\times\mathbf{C}^{2}}{\int}d\Delta\wedge dz\wedge d\bar{z}\,\,\,\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{\Delta}\left(\xi^{\alpha}\right)\mathcal{F}_{\Delta}\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

In this expression, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}$
\end_inset

 denotes the restriction of the Dolbeault operator to the minitwistor superline
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{T}^{a}$
\end_inset

 represents a generator of the Lie algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

, the domain of integration 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\coloneqq1+i\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the continuous principal series, where the celestial conformal
 weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 resides, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{\Delta}\left(\xi^{\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the Mellin-transformed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 superfield introduced in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-52"

\end_inset

), and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\Delta}\in\Omega^{0,1}\left(\mathbf{MT},\mathcal{O}\left(-2,-\Delta\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 the minitwistor wavefunction defined in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-22"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step in our derivation consists in observing that the Penrose
 integral-geometric transform of the minitwistor background potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset

 is expressed as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}{\int}\,\boldsymbol{\omega}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\left(\lambda\right)\,=\,\mathsf{T}^{a}\underset{\mathcal{P}\times\mathbf{C}^{2}}{\int}d\Delta\wedge dz\wedge d\bar{z}\,\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{\Delta}\left(\xi^{\alpha}\right)\,K_{\Delta}\left(X;z,\bar{z}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\Delta}\left(X;z,\bar{z}\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes the bulk-to-boundary propagator on the hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

 expressed in terms of homogeneous coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 that chart real projective superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Accordingly, we can apply the celestial BMS identity established in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-18"

\end_inset

) to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To proceed, we employ the expansion of the Quillen determinant, as explained
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "boels2007twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mason2010complete,mason2010gravity,mason2010scattering,bullimore2010mhv"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Upon applying the celestial BMS identity, we find that the generating functiona
l admits the expansion:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \digamma[\boldsymbol{\omega}]=\sum_{m\geq2}\frac{\left(-1\right)^{m+1}}{m}\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}}{\int}D^{3|8}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\mathsf{Tr}\underset{(\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right))^{\times n}}{\int}\,\bigwedge_{i=1}^{m}D\lambda_{i}\,\,\,\boldsymbol{\omega}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,\,\,\frac{1}{\lambda_{i}\cdot\lambda_{i+1}}\\
 & =\sum_{m\geq2}\frac{\left(-1\right)^{m+1}}{m}\underset{\left(\mathcal{P}\times\mathbf{C}^{2}\right)^{\times m}}{\int}\,\bigwedge_{r=1}^{m}\,\boldsymbol{\beta}_{r}\,\,\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}}{\int}\,D^{3|8}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\mathsf{Tr}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{\Delta_{i}}\left(\xi_{i}^{\alpha}\right)\,K_{\Delta_{i}}\left(X;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\,\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{a_{i}}}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}},
\end{align}

\end_inset

where:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\beta}_{r}\,\coloneqq\,d\Delta_{r}\wedge dz_{r}\wedge d\bar{z}_{r}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To complete the derivation, we perform functional differentiation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\digamma\left[\boldsymbol{\omega}\right]$
\end_inset

 with respect to the classical expectation values of the annihilation operators
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{a}_{\Delta_{i}}^{\ell_{i}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

, which correspond to gluon states with helicity 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{i}$
\end_inset

 and celestial conformal weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{i}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta}{\delta\mathsf{a}_{2h_{i}}^{\ell_{1}}\left(z_{i}\right)}...\frac{\delta}{\delta\mathsf{a}_{\Delta_{n}}^{\ell_{n}}\left(z_{n},\bar{z}_{n}\right)}\digamma\left[\boldsymbol{\omega}\right]\Bigg|_{\boldsymbol{\varphi}=0}=\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}}{\int}D^{3|8}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\mathsf{Tr}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\boldsymbol{\varphi}\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)\,K_{2h_{i}}\left(X;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\frac{\mathsf{T}^{a_{i}}}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The resulting expression is immediately recognised as the gluonic leaf amplitude
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}^{a_{1}...a_{n}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We conclude that the formalism constructed in this subsection in terms
 of the minitwistor background potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset

 provides a generating functional for tree-level MHV scattering amplitudes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Geometrical Interpretation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\left(X,\theta\right)}:\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 be the canonical projection.
 The embedding of the celestial sphere, modelled by the holomorphic Riemann
 sphere, into minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

 as a minitwistor superline 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as a section 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\left(X,\theta\right)}$
\end_inset

 of the fibration.
 In fact, by trivialising the fibration 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\left(X,\theta\right)}$
\end_inset

 using homogeneous coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

, we define the map:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma:\mathbf{CP}^{1}\longrightarrow\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which acts as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma:\lambda^{A}\mapsto\left(\lambda^{A},\lambda^{A}\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|},\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is obvious that this mapping satisfies the section condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\left(X,\theta\right)}\circ\sigma_{\left(X,\theta\right)}=id_{\mathbf{CP}^{1}}$
\end_inset

 by construction.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\left(X,\theta\right)}$
\end_inset

 is also an embedding of the celestial sphere into the Hitchin-special supercurv
e 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)\subset\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This simple observation has an important implication for the interpretation
 of the generating functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\digamma\left[\boldsymbol{\omega}\right]$
\end_inset

, which involves an integral of the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}}{\int}D^{3|8}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}{\int}(...)\,\,\,.\label{eq:-53}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A careful analysis shows that this expression 
\emph on
should not
\emph default
 be interpreted as integrating over celestial 
\emph on
spheres
\emph default
 at each point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{X}^{\hat{I}}\in\mathbf{RP}^{3|8}$
\end_inset

.
 Instead, the correct interpretation is that the integral is taken over
 the space of all 
\emph on
embeddings
\emph default
 of the celestial sphere into the minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-53"

\end_inset

) should be regarded as an integral over the moduli space of embeddings
 of the celestial sphere.
 This interpretation has important consequences for the construction of
 the on-shell effective action of our sigma model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:-Supergravity"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our analysis begins with the Berends-Giele-Kuijf (BGK) formula
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Originally derived in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "berends1988relations"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which describes the tree-level gravitational scattering amplitudes for
 configurations characterised by maximal helicity violation.
 Consider a scattering process involving 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 gravitons in the MHV configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{--},2^{--},3^{++},...,n^{++}$
\end_inset

, for which the amplitude is expressed as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{M}_{n}\left(z_{i},\overline{z}_{i},s_{i}\right)\,=\,\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^{n-2}\,\delta^{\left(4\right)}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}\nu_{i}^{A}\bar{\nu}_{i}^{\dot{A}}\right)\,\,\,BGK_{n},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $BGK_{n}$
\end_inset

 factor is defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
BGK_{n}\coloneqq\frac{\left\langle \nu_{1}\nu_{2}\right\rangle ^{8}}{\prod_{r=1}^{n}\nu_{r}\cdot\nu_{r+1}}\frac{1}{\left\langle \nu_{n}\nu_{1}\right\rangle \left\langle \nu_{1}\nu_{n-1}\right\rangle \left\langle \nu_{n-1}\nu_{n}\right\rangle }\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\frac{[\bar{\nu}_{i}|p_{i+1}+...+p_{n-1}|\nu_{n}\rangle}{\nu_{i}\cdot\nu_{n}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A specially enlightening modern derivation of this result, using Plebanski's
 second heavenly equation, was given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "miller2024proof"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our objective is to apply the formalism of celestial leaf amplitudes to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the minitwistor wavefunctions developed in Subsection (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Minitwistor-Wavefunctions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), we seek to recast the modified Mellin transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{n}$
\end_inset

 into a form that admits an interpretation as an integral over a moduli
 space of minitwistor lines.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 Fermionic Doublet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The factorisation procedure to be employed in this section is based on the
 method developed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "nair2005note"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this formalism, tree-level MHV gravitational scattering amplitudes are
 expressed in terms of a correlator of ``vertex operators.'' These operators
 are constructed with the aid of an auxiliary fermionic doublet 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}},\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

, and their explicit forms are determined by the following mode expansions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}\left(z\right)\,\coloneqq\,\sum_{p\geq0}\,\frac{\mathsf{b}_{p}}{z^{1+p}},\,\,\,\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}^{\dagger}\left(z\right)\,\coloneqq\,\sum_{p\geq0}\,z^{p}\,\mathsf{b}_{p}^{\dagger}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, the fermionic annihilation and creation operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{b}_{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{b}_{p}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the anti-commutation relations 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathsf{b}_{p},\mathsf{b}_{q}^{\dagger}\}=\delta_{pq}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\geq0$
\end_inset

, and their action on the vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{b}_{p}|0\rangle=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For notational convenience, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{i}\coloneqq\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}\left(z_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{i}^{\dagger}\coloneqq\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}^{\dagger}\left(z_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

, where the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the holomorphic coordinates that parametrise the momenta
 of the gravitons participating in the scattering process under consideration.
 Boldface symbols are employed for the fermionic fields to emphasise their
 operator character, and, as will be demonstrated, their correlators will
 serve to reconstruct the graviton amplitudes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The anti-commutation relations imply that the two-point correlation function
 of the doublet 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}},\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

 assumes the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle0|\,\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{i}\,\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{j}^{\dagger}\,|0\rangle\,=\,\frac{1}{z_{ij}},\,\,\,z_{ij}\,\coloneqq\,z_{i}-z_{j}.\label{eq:-5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to introduce the graviton vertex operators, it is useful to reformulate
 the fermionic system 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}},\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

 in terms of an alternative representation, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{\chi},\boldsymbol{\chi}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

, which is defined on the holomorphic vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)\oplus\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 of undotted two-component spinors.
 The precise correspondence between these two representations is specified
 as follows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{A}$
\end_inset

 denote a two-component spinor, and consider a local trivialisation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{\mathscr{U}}$
\end_inset

 of the bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)\oplus\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nu^{A})_{\mathscr{U}}=\left(\alpha,\beta\right)^{T}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in\mathbf{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Within the trivialisation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}$
\end_inset

, it is natural to projectively represent 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{A}$
\end_inset

 on the complex projective line by introducing the local affine coordinate
 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[z]\coloneqq[\alpha\beta^{-1}]\in\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 With these preliminary observations in place, we define:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\chi}\left(\nu\right)\,\coloneqq\,\beta^{-1}\,\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}\left(z\right),\,\,\,\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}^{\dagger}\left(\nu\right)\,\coloneqq\,\beta^{-1}\,\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}^{\dagger}\left(z\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For notational convenience, we introduce the shorthand 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{i}\coloneqq\boldsymbol{\chi}\left(z_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{i}^{\dagger}\coloneqq\boldsymbol{\chi}^{\dagger}\left(z_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z_{i}^{A},\overline{z}_{i\dot{A}}\}$
\end_inset

 constitutes a normalised spinor basis, defined explicitly by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z_{i}^{A}\,\coloneqq\,\begin{pmatrix}1\\
z_{i}
\end{pmatrix},\,\,\,\overline{z}_{i\dot{A}}\,\coloneqq\,\begin{pmatrix}\,\overline{z}_{i}\,\,\, & \,\,\,-1\,\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Similarly, we employ the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{i}}\coloneqq\boldsymbol{\chi}\left(\nu_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{i}}^{\dagger}\coloneqq\boldsymbol{\chi}^{\dagger}\left(\nu_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

, where the spinors 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{i}^{A}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\leq i\leq n\right)$
\end_inset

 parametrise the kinematical data associated with the momenta of the graviton
 states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given these definitions, the two-point correlation function of the fermionic
 doublet 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{\chi},\boldsymbol{\chi}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

 may be expressed simply as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle0|\,\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{i}}\,\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{j}}^{\dagger}\,|0\rangle\,=\,\frac{1}{\nu_{i}\cdot\nu_{j}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $BGK_{n}$
\end_inset

 Formula from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 Correlators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The graviton ``vertex operators'' are defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{G}_{i}\,\coloneqq\,\exp\big(\,i\,\langle\nu_{i}|\,x\,|\overline{\nu}_{i}]\,\big)\,\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{i}}^{\dagger}\,\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{i}},\,\,\:\mathcal{H}_{i}\,\coloneqq\,\frac{[\overline{\nu}_{i}|\left(-i\boldsymbol{\partial}\right)|\omega\rangle}{\nu_{i}\cdot\omega}\,\exp\big(\,i\,\langle\nu_{i}|\,x\,|\overline{\nu}_{i}]\,\big).\label{eq:-19}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the above expressions, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{\partial})_{A\dot{A}}\coloneqq(\sigma^{\mu})_{A\dot{A}}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\mu}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{A}\,\coloneqq\,\left(\frac{i}{2\pi}\right)^{1/2}\,\left(\,\omega,\,-1\,\right)$
\end_inset

 is an auxiliary two-component spinor parametrised by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\omega\right]\in\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This spinor serves as a reference variable over which integration is performed
 in the final expressions involving the correlation functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, the spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{A}$
\end_inset

 defines a state-vector within the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 fermionic system 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{\chi},\boldsymbol{\chi}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

, which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $|\omega\rangle\coloneqq\chi^{\dagger}\left(\omega\right)|0\rangle.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through an inductive argument on 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

, it can be established that the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{i}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the identity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \mathcal{G}_{1}\,\left(\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\mathcal{H}_{i}\right)\,\mathcal{G}_{n-1}\,\mathcal{G}_{n}\\
 & =\,\,\,e^{i\left(p_{1}+...+p_{n}\right)\cdot x}\,\,\,\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\,\frac{[\overline{\nu}_{i}|p_{i+1}+...+p_{n}|\omega\rangle}{\nu_{i}\cdot\omega}\,\,\,\big(\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{1}}^{\dagger}\,\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{1}}\big)\,\big(\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{n-1}}^{\dagger}\,\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{n-1}}\big)\,\big(\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{n}}^{\dagger}\,\boldsymbol{\chi}_{\nu_{n}}\big).
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This property implies an integral relation satisfied by the correlation
 functions of the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{i}$
\end_inset

, which is expressed as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \frac{1}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\,\,\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{4}}{\int}\,\,\,d^{4}x\,\,\,\underset{\mathscr{C}_{n}}{\oint}\,\,\,\left\langle \omega d\omega\right\rangle \,\,\,\langle\omega|\,\mathcal{G}_{1}\left(\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\mathcal{H}_{i}\right)\mathcal{G}_{n-1}\,\mathcal{G}_{n}\,|\omega\rangle\\
 & =\,\,\,\delta^{\left(4\right)}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}\nu_{i}^{A}\bar{\nu}_{i}^{\dot{A}}\right)\,\frac{1}{\left\langle \nu_{n}\nu_{1}\right\rangle \left\langle \nu_{1}\nu_{n-1}\right\rangle \left\langle \nu_{n-1}\nu_{n}\right\rangle }\,\prod_{j=2}^{n-2}\,\frac{[\bar{\nu}_{j}|p_{j+1}+...+p_{n-1}|\nu_{n}\rangle}{\nu_{j}\cdot\nu_{n}},
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}_{n}$
\end_inset

 denotes a small contour centred at the insertion point on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 representing the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th graviton.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, the scattering amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{n}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in a form structurally reminiscent of the correlation
 functions of vertex operators in conventional twistor string theory
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See, e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "abou2008einstein,adamo2013twistor,mason2014ambitwistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{M}_{n}\,=\,\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^{2}\,\,\,\left\langle \nu_{1}\nu_{2}\right\rangle ^{8}\,\,\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{4}}{\int}\,\,\,\frac{d^{4}x}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\,\,\,\underset{\mathscr{C}_{n}}{\oint}\,\left\langle \omega d\omega\right\rangle \,\,\,\langle\omega|\,\mathcal{G}_{1}\,\left(\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\mathcal{H}_{i}\right)\,\mathcal{G}_{n-1}\,\mathcal{G}_{n}\,|\omega\rangle\,\,\,\prod_{j=1}^{n}\frac{1}{\nu_{j}\cdot\nu_{j+1}}.\label{eq:-7}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The precise nature of this correspondence will be clarified in the subsequent
 sections.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Frequency Dependency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To proceed with our aim of performing the Mellin transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{n}$
\end_inset

, thereby yielding the corresponding celestial amplitude, it is necessary
 to re-express Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-7"

\end_inset

) explicitly in terms of the graviton frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the normalised spinor basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z_{i}^{A},\overline{z}_{i\dot{A}}\}$
\end_inset

.
 This reformulation takes the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{M}_{n}\,=\,\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^{n-2}\,\,\,\left(z_{1}\cdot z_{2}\right)^{8}\,\,\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{4}}{\int}\,\frac{d^{4}x}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\,\,\,\underset{\mathscr{C}_{n}}{\oint}\,\left\langle \omega d\omega\right\rangle \,\,\,\langle\omega|\,\mathcal{G}_{1}\left(\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\mathcal{H}_{i}\right)\mathcal{G}_{n-1}\,\mathcal{G}_{n}\,|\omega\rangle\,\,\,\prod_{j=1}^{n}\frac{s_{j}^{e_{j}}}{z_{j}\cdot z_{j+1}}.\label{eq:-6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In this expression, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\leq i\leq n\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes the set of exponents characterising the powers in which the frequencies
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 appear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For the MHV configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{--},2^{--},3^{++},...,n^{++}$
\end_inset

, these exponents are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1}=e_{2}=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{3}=...=e_{n}=-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we proceed, the analysis transitions from the MHV amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{n}$
\end_inset

 to the graviton super-amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{M}_{n}$
\end_inset

 within the onshell superspace formalism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity.
 To maintain generality throughout the derivation, we shall retain the explicit
 dependence on the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 in all subsequent equations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transition from Einstein's gravity to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity is facilitated by adopting the on-shell superfield formalism,
 as reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wess2020supersymmetry"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
On-shell Superfield Expansion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formalism introduces Grassmann-valued two-component spinors, denoted
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{A}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\leq\alpha\leq8\right)$
\end_inset

 and normalised according to the relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{R}^{0|2}}{\int}\,d^{0|2}\eta\,\,\,\eta_{A}^{\alpha}\,\eta_{B}^{\alpha}=\varepsilon_{AB}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To construct the requisite supermultiplets, we define the set of Grassmann-value
d coefficients:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}\coloneqq z_{i}\cdot\eta^{\alpha}\,\,\,\left(1\leq\alpha\leq8\right).\label{eq:-39}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 By employing the properties of the Berezin-de Witt integral, the following
 identity is established:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\big(z_{i}\cdot z_{j}\big)^{8}\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{0|16}}{\int}\,d^{0|16}\eta\,\prod_{\alpha=1}^{8}\,\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}\zeta_{j}^{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which permits the following reformulation of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-6"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{M}_{n}=\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^{n-2}\int\,\frac{d^{4}x}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\,\wedge\,d^{0|16}\eta\,\prod_{\alpha=1}^{8}\zeta_{1}^{\alpha}\zeta_{2}^{\alpha}\underset{\mathscr{C}_{n}}{\oint}\left\langle \omega d\omega\right\rangle \langle\omega|\,\mathcal{G}_{1}\left(\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\mathcal{H}_{i}\right)\mathcal{G}_{n-1}\,\mathcal{G}_{n}\,|\omega\rangle\prod_{j=1}^{n}\frac{s_{j}^{e_{j}}}{z_{j}\cdot z_{j+1}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The particle spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity is described by the superfield 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

, which parametrises all one-particle states of the theory.
 This superfield may be expanded as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{i}(\zeta_{i}^{\alpha})\,=\,\mathsf{h}^{-}\,+\,\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}\,\widetilde{\lambda}_{\alpha}\,+\,\frac{1}{2!}\,\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}\,\zeta_{i}^{\beta}\,\,\,\widetilde{\phi}_{\alpha\beta}\,+\,...\,+\,\mathsf{h}_{i}^{+}\,\,\,\prod_{\alpha=1}^{8}\,\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{h}_{i}^{-}\coloneqq\mathsf{h}^{-}\left(z,\bar{z}_{i},s_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 represents the classical expectation value associated with the annihilation
 operator of a graviton of negative helicity, with momentum parametrised
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\mu}=s_{i}q\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{h}_{i}^{+}\coloneqq\mathsf{h}^{+}\left(z_{i},\overline{z}_{i},s_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes the analogous quantity for a graviton of positive helicity.
 The intermediate terms in this expansion describe the remaining one-particle
 states in the supermultiplet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Superspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this stage, it is pertinent to specify the structure of the superspace
 on which the graviton super-amplitude is formulated.
 Thus, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{4|16}$
\end_inset

 denote the supersymmetric extension of the four-dimensional Euclidean space
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

, obtained by appending to the bosonic coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 the set of Grassmann-odd spinorial coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{A}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha=1,...,8\right)$
\end_inset

.
 These fermionic ``dimensions,'' together with the bosonic ones, are collectivel
y encoded in the supercoordinates
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We follow standard conventions in abstract index notation.
 In addition, indices associated with supercoordinates, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\text{I}},\hat{\text{J}},...$
\end_inset

, are adorned with a hat to distinguish them from the minitwistor indices
 
\begin_inset Formula $I,J,...$
\end_inset

 appearing in expressions involving the minitwistor representatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Y}_{I},\mathsf{Z}^{J},$
\end_inset

 etc.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{x}^{\hat{\text{I}}}\coloneqq\left(x^{\mu},\eta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The supermanifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{4|16}$
\end_inset

 is endowed with the canonical orientation defined by the Berezin-de Witt
 volume superform:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d^{4|16}\,\mathsf{x}\,\coloneqq\,d^{4}x\,\wedge\,d^{0|16}\theta.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Accordingly, the graviton super-amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{M}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is expressed in the on-shell superfield formalism as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathscr{M}_{n}\,=\,\frac{1}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^{n-2}\underset{\mathbf{R}^{4|16}}{\int}d^{4|16}\mathsf{x}\,\underset{\mathscr{C}_{n}}{\oint}\,\left\langle \omega d\omega\right\rangle \,\langle\omega|\,\mathcal{G}_{1}\left(\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\mathcal{H}_{i}\right)\mathcal{G}_{n-1}\,\mathcal{G}_{n}\,|\omega\rangle\,\prod_{j=1}^{n}\psi\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)\,\frac{s_{j}^{e_{j}}}{z_{j}\cdot z_{j+1}}.\label{eq:-8}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Celestial Leaf Amplitudes for Gravitons
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the requisite mathematical preliminaries established, we now begin
 our analysis of graviton celestial amplitudes.
 The main objective it to demonstrate that the gravitational leaf amplitudes
 can be interpreted as an integral over the moduli space of minitwistor
 lines on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 supersymmetric extension of minitwistor space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|8}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mellin Transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first recall that the celestial superamplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathscr{M}}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 for gravitons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity is defined as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

-regulated Mellin transform of the corresponding scattering amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{M}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},s_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

, as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathscr{M}}_{n}\left(z_{i},\overline{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\,\,\,\coloneqq\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\underset{\mathbf{R}_{+}^{\times}}{\int}\,\frac{ds_{i}}{s_{i}}\,s_{i}^{\Delta_{i}}\,e^{-\varepsilon s_{i}}\,\,\,\mathscr{M}_{n}\left(z_{i},\overline{z}_{i},s_{i}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}_{+}^{\times}$
\end_inset

 denotes the multiplicative group of positive real numbers, and the integral
 is taken with respect to the Haar measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{ds_{i}}{s_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now introduce the 
\emph on
Mellin-transformed graviton vertex operators
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathcal{G}}_{i}\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{R}_{+}^{\times}}{\int}\,\frac{ds_{i}}{s_{i}^{1-e_{i}-\Delta_{i}}}\,\,\,e^{-\varepsilon s_{i}}\,\mathcal{G}_{i},\,\,\,\widehat{\mathcal{H}}_{i}\coloneqq\underset{\mathbf{R}_{+}^{\times}}{\int}\,\frac{ds_{i}}{s_{i}^{1-e_{i}-\Delta_{i}}}\,\,\,e^{-\varepsilon s_{i}}\,\mathcal{H}_{i}.\label{eq:-20}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In these definitions, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\leq i\leq n\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes exponents characterising the frequency dependence of the super-amplitud
e 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{M}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to these vertex operators, we define the 
\emph on
Mellin-transformed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 superfield 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\psi}_{\Delta_{i}}\left(\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\psi}_{\Delta_{i}}\left(\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\widehat{\mathsf{h}}_{\Delta_{i}}^{-}\left(z_{i},\overline{z}_{i}\right)\,+\,\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}\,\widehat{\lambda}_{\alpha,\Delta_{i}}\left(z_{i},\overline{z}_{i}\right)\,+\,\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}\zeta_{i}^{\beta}\,\widehat{\phi}_{\alpha\beta,\Delta_{i}}\,+\,...\,+\widehat{\mathsf{h}}_{\Delta_{i}}^{+}\left(z_{i},\overline{z}_{i}\right)\,\,\,\prod_{\alpha=1}^{8}\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}.\label{eq:-45}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The modes of the superfield expansion now explicitly depend on the celestial
 conformal weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By substituting the expressions from Eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-19"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-20"

\end_inset

), and subsequently performing the integral transforms, we obtain the following
 explicit forms of the Mellin-transformed vertex operators:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathcal{G}}_{i}\,=\,\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(x;z_{i},\overline{z}_{i}\right)\,\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{i}^{\dagger}\,\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{i},\,\,\,\widehat{\mathcal{H}}_{i}\,=\,\frac{[\overline{z}_{i}\big|\left(-i\boldsymbol{\partial}\right)\big|\omega\rangle}{z_{i}\cdot\omega}\,\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(x;z_{i},\overline{z}_{i}\right),\label{eq:-54}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\Delta}\left(x;z,\overline{z}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the celestial wavefunction defined in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-46"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The scaling dimensions of these operators are given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h_{i}=\frac{\Delta_{i}+e_{i}-1}{2},\,\,\,h_{j}\coloneqq\frac{\Delta_{j}+e_{j}}{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, the celestial superamplitude for gravitons can be expressed
 in the following integral form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathscr{M}}_{n}=\frac{1}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^{n-2}\underset{\mathbf{R}^{4|16}}{\int}d^{4|16}\mathsf{w}\,\,\,\underset{\mathscr{C}_{n}}{\oint}\,\left\langle \omega d\omega\right\rangle \,\langle\omega|\,\widehat{\mathcal{G}}_{1}\left(\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\widehat{\mathcal{H}}_{i}\right)\widehat{\mathcal{G}}_{n-1}\,\widehat{\mathcal{G}}_{n}\,|\omega\rangle\,\prod_{j=1}^{n}\frac{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2h_{j}}\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)}{z_{j}\cdot z_{j+1}}.\label{eq:-8-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gravitational Celestial Leaf Amplitudes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To reformulate the graviton celestial amplitude as an integral over the
 moduli space of minitwistor lines, we employ the formalism of leaf amplitudes.
 However, a technical complication immediately presents itself: the celestial
 wavefunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(x;z_{i},\overline{z}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

, which appear as multiplicative factors in the vertex operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathcal{G}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathcal{H}}_{i}$
\end_inset

, are currently enclosed within the fixed-ordering correlator 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\omega|\cdot\cdot\cdot|\omega\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 It is necessary to extract these wavefunctions from the correlator, as
 this step permits the separation of the spacetime integral from the contour
 integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\oint_{\mathscr{C}_{n}}\left\langle \omega d\omega\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, thus making it possible to apply the leaf amplitude formalism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We proceed by implementing the following strategy.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{P}_{i}$
\end_inset

 denote the 
\emph on
weight-shifting operator
\emph default
 acting on the Hilbert space of celestial wavefunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 The action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{P}_{i}$
\end_inset

 on a given wavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\Delta_{j}}\left(x;z_{j},\bar{z}_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{P}_{i}\,\cdot\,\phi_{\Delta_{j}}\left(x;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\phi_{\Delta_{j}+\delta_{ij}}\left(x;z_{j},\bar{z}_{j}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Consequently, we define a new set of graviton vertex operators:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}_{i}\coloneqq\exp\big(-\langle z_{i}\big|y\big|\overline{z}_{i}]\,\mathsf{P}_{i}\big)\,\,\,\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{i}^{\dagger}\,\hat{\boldsymbol{\chi}}_{i},\,\,\,\mathcal{V}_{i}\coloneqq\frac{[\bar{z}_{i}\big|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\partial}}\big|\omega\rangle}{z_{i}\cdot\omega}\,\,\,\exp\big(-\langle z_{i}\big|y\big|\overline{z}_{i}]\,\mathsf{P}_{i}\big).\label{eq:-25}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the above expression, 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\mu}\in\mathbf{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 denotes an 
\emph on
auxiliary 
\emph default
four-vector that parametrises the operator family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathcal{U}_{i},\mathcal{V}_{i}\}$
\end_inset

.
 The partial derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\partial}}$
\end_inset

 acts with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\mu}$
\end_inset

, and is defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\big(\,\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\partial}}\,\big)_{A\dot{A}}\coloneqq(\boldsymbol{\sigma}^{\mu})_{A\dot{A}}\frac{\partial}{\partial y^{\mu}}\,\,\,(y^{\mu}\in\mathbf{R}^{4}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{\sigma}^{\mu})_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 represents the sigma matrices in the Kleinian signature, defined in Appendix
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Leaf-Amplitudes-Review"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to emphasise that the four-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 should be regarded solely as a continuous label indexing the operator family.
 It does not carry the interpretation of a spacetime coordinate.
 Moreover, in all subsequent expressions where 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 appears, the final evaluation is to be performed at 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\mu}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now establish, through an inductive argument on 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

, that the vertex operators satisfy the following algebraic identity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathcal{G}}_{1}\,\left(\,\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\,\widehat{\mathcal{H}}_{i}\,\right)\,\widehat{\mathcal{G}}_{n-1}\,\widehat{\mathcal{G}}_{n}\,\,\,=\,\,\,\mathcal{U}_{1}\,\left(\,\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\,\mathcal{V}_{i}\,\right)\,\mathcal{U}_{n-1}\mathcal{U}_{n}\,\,\,\prod_{j=1}^{n}\phi_{2h_{j}}\left(x;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this equality, it follows that the celestial super-amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathscr{M}}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 can be reformulated as a correlator involving the newly introduced graviton
 vertex operators:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\widehat{\mathscr{M}}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\, & =\,\frac{1}{\left(2\pi\right)^{4}}\,\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^{n-2}\,\underset{\mathscr{C}_{n}}{\oint}\,\left\langle \omega d\omega\right\rangle \,\,\,\langle\omega|\,\mathcal{U}_{1}\left(\prod_{r=2}^{n-2}\mathcal{V}_{r}\right)\mathcal{U}_{n-1}\mathcal{U}_{n}\,|\omega\rangle\,\\
 & \times\,\underset{\mathbf{R}^{4|16}}{\int}\,\,\,d^{4|16}\mathsf{x}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\,\,\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2h_{i}}\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)\,\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(x;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\,\,\frac{1}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final step required prior to the application of the leaf amplitude formalism
 is to specify the integration domain over which it is defined.
 In Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Minitwistor-Geometry"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we review how the Riemannian geometry of the hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

 arises from the projective geometry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 denote homogeneous coordinates charting the real projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The natural orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is given by the volume form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{3}X\,=\,\varepsilon_{A\dot{A}}\varepsilon_{B\dot{B}}\varepsilon_{C\dot{C}}\varepsilon_{D\dot{D}}\,X^{A\dot{A}}dX^{B\dot{B}}\wedge dX^{C\dot{C}}\wedge dX^{D\dot{D}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3,16\right)$
\end_inset

-dimensional real projective 
\emph on
superspace
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}$
\end_inset

 is obtained by augmenting the bosonic coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 with Grassmann-valued spinorial variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{A}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1,...,8$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the coordinates of the resulting superchart
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We follow the terminology of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rogers2007supermanifolds"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 See also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "leites1980introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "manin1997introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{X}^{\hat{I}}\coloneqq\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)\in\mathbf{RP}^{3}\times\mathbf{R}^{0|16}$
\end_inset

.
 The natural orientation of the supermanifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}$
\end_inset

 is defined by the Berezin-de Witt volume superform:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{3|16}\mathbb{X}\,\coloneqq\,\frac{D^{3}X}{\left|X\right|^{4}}\wedge d^{0|16}\zeta.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now prepared to employ the celestial leaf amplitude formalism, reviewed
 in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Leaf-Amplitudes-Review"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which permits to recast 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathscr{M}}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathscr{M}}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\,=\,\frac{1}{\left(2\pi\right)^{3}}\,\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^{n-2}\delta\left(\beta\right)\,\times\,M_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\,+\,(\bar{z}_{i\dot{A}}\longrightarrow-\bar{z}_{i\dot{A}}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\coloneqq4-2\sum_{i=1}^{n}h_{i}$
\end_inset

, and the graviton leaf amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{n}\,=\,\underset{\mathscr{C}_{n}}{\oint}\left\langle \omega d\omega\right\rangle \,\,\,\langle\omega|\,\mathcal{U}_{1}\,\left(\,\prod_{r=2}^{n-2}\,\mathcal{V}_{r}\,\right)\,\mathcal{U}_{n-1}\mathcal{U}_{n}\,|\omega\rangle\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}}{\int}\,D^{3|16}\,\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,K_{2h_{i}}\left(X;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\,\,\frac{\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2h_{i}}\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Celestial RSVW Formalism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to find a geometrical interpretation for the gravitational leaf
 amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 To achieve this, it proves useful to employ the following decomposition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\,\,\,=\,\,\,\fintop\,dh_{1}...dh_{n}\,\,\,\text{m}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},h_{i}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\,\fintop\,dh_{1}...dh_{n}$
\end_inset

 denotes a weight-shifting ``integral'' operator, defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\fintop\,dh_{1}...dh_{n}\,\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathscr{C}_{n}}{\oint}\left\langle \omega d\omega\right\rangle \,\,\,\langle\omega|\,\mathcal{U}_{1}\,\left(\,\prod_{r=2}^{n-2}\,\mathcal{V}_{r}\,\right)\,\mathcal{U}_{n-1}\mathcal{U}_{n}\,|\omega\rangle\,,\label{eq:-47}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the ``reduced'' leaf amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{m}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},h_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{m}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},h_{i}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}}{\int}\,D^{3|16}\,\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2h_{i}}\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)\,K_{2h_{i}}\left(X;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\,\,\frac{1}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.\label{eq:-15}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-25"

\end_inset

), which defines the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{i}$
\end_inset

, and applying it to the contour integral in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-47"

\end_inset

), we deduce the following expression for the weight-shifting ``integral''
 operator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\fintop\,dh_{1}...dh_{n}\,=\,\left(-1\right)^{n+1}\,\left(\prod_{i=2}^{n-2}\sum_{j_{i}=i+1}^{n-1}\right)\,\prod_{k=2}^{n-2}\,\frac{[\bar{z}_{k}\bar{z}_{j_{k}}]\langle z_{j_{k}}z_{n}\rangle}{z_{k}\cdot z_{n}}\,\mathsf{P}_{j_{k}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This equation establishes that 
\begin_inset Formula $\fintop\,dh_{1}...dh_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial constructed from a sequence of weight-shifting operators
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{P}_{i}$
\end_inset

, acting on the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}_{c}$
\end_inset

 of celestial wavefunctions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Celestial RSVW Formula for Gravitons
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our derivation of the celestial RSVW formula for gravitational leaf amplitudes
 begins with the resolution of the identity for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 superfield:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2h_{i}}\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)\,\,\,=\,\,\,\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{0|8}}{\int}\,d^{0|8}\zeta_{i}\,\,\,\delta^{\left(8\right)}\left(\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}-z_{i}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)\,\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2h_{i}}\left(\zeta_{i}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{0|8}\zeta$
\end_inset

 denotes the Berezin-de Witt integral over the fermionic coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 This identity allows us to reformulate the ``reduced'' leaf amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{m}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 defined in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-15"

\end_inset

) as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{m}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right) & \,\,\,=\,\,\,\prod_{r=1}^{n}\,\,\,\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{0|8}}{\int}\,\,\,d^{0|8}\zeta_{r}\,\,\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}}{\int}\,\,\,D^{3|16}\mathbb{X}\\
 & \prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\,\,\delta^{\left(8\right)}\left(\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}-z_{i}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)\,\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2h_{i}}\left(\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}\right)\,K_{2h_{i}}\left(X;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\,\,\frac{1}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To proceed, we introduce local coordinates charting the minitwistor space
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbf{MT}\mapsto\mathsf{Z}^{I}\left(p\right)\coloneqq\left(\lambda^{A}\left(p\right),\mu_{\dot{A}}\left(p\right)\right)\in\mathbf{CP}^{1}\times\overline{\mathbf{CP}}^{1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 are homogeneous coordinates on the complex projective lines 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbf{CP}}^{1}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Recall that the minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 is a non-singular quadric in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

, and its canonical orientation is induced by the volume form 
\begin_inset Formula $D\lambda\wedge D\mu$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $D\lambda\coloneqq\varepsilon_{AB}\lambda^{A}d\lambda^{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D\mathcal{\mu}\coloneqq\varepsilon^{\dot{A}\dot{B}}\mu_{\dot{A}}d\mu_{\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now invoke the celestial RSVW identity derived in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-49"

\end_inset

), which allows us to rewrite the expression for the ``reduced'' leaf amplitude
 in terms of integrals over minitwistor space:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{m}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right) & \,=\,\prod_{r=1}^{n}\,\,\,\underset{\mathbf{MT}\times\mathbf{CP}^{0|8}}{\int}\,\,\,D\lambda_{r}\wedge D\mu_{r}\wedge d^{0|8}\zeta_{r}\,\,\,\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2h_{r}}\left(\zeta_{r}^{\alpha}\right)\,\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{2h_{r}}\left(\lambda_{r}^{A},\mu_{r\dot{A}};z_{r}^{A},\bar{z}_{r\dot{A}}\right)\label{eq:-55}\\
 & \underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}}{\int}\,D^{3|16}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\,\,\overline{\delta}_{2h_{i}}\left(\mu_{i\dot{A}},\lambda_{i}^{A}\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}\right)\,\delta^{\left(8\right)}\left(\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}-\lambda_{i}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)\,\,\,\frac{1}{\lambda_{i}\cdot\lambda_{i+1}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The subsequent step in our derivation requires a specification of the domain
 over which the ``reduced'' gravitational leaf amplitude is defined.
 Observe that the first integrals appearing in the above expression are
 taken over the product space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}\times\mathbf{CP}^{0|8}$
\end_inset

.
 As will be discussed in detail in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Minitwistor-String-Theories"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, where our sigma model is introduced, the minitwistor superspace
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a rigorous mathematical discussion, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "samann2009mini"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is identified with the trivial superbundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|8}\simeq\mathbf{MT}\times\mathbf{CP}^{0|8}$
\end_inset

.
 Here, the base manifold is the nonsingular quadric, while the typical fibre
 isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{0|8}$
\end_inset

 follows from the projectivisation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded vector space spanned by the Grassmann-valued homogeneous coordinates
 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1,...,8$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The orientation on the total space of this superbundle is defined by the
 Berezin-de Witt volume superform:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{2|8}\mathsf{Z}\,\coloneqq\,D\lambda\wedge D\mu\wedge d^{0|8}\zeta.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following Witten's original construction
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "witten2004perturbative,edward2004parity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the 
\emph on
minitwistor wavefunction
\emph default
 associated with a graviton of 
\emph on
celestial conformal weight
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 is identified from Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-55"

\end_inset

) as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\Delta}\left(\mathsf{Z}^{I};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{\Delta}\left(\zeta^{\alpha}\right)\,\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{\Delta}\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}};z^{A},\bar{z}_{\dot{A}}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Consequently, the ``reduced'' gravitational leaf amplitude can be expressed
 as a Fourier transform over minitwistor superspace:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{m}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\,=\,\underset{\left(\mathbf{MT}^{2|8}\right)^{\times n}}{\int}\,\bigwedge_{i=1}^{n}\,D^{2|8}\mathsf{Z}_{i}\,\,\,\Phi_{2h_{i}}\left(\mathsf{Z}_{i};z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\widetilde{\text{m}}_{n}\left(\mathsf{Z}_{i}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the Fourier-transformed amplitude is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\text{m}}_{n}\left(\mathsf{Z}_{i}\right)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}}{\int}D^{3|16}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\,\,\overline{\delta}_{2h_{i}}\left(\mu_{i\dot{A}},\lambda_{i}^{A}\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}\right)\,\delta^{\left(8\right)}\left(\zeta_{i}^{\alpha}-\lambda_{i}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)\,\,\,\frac{1}{\lambda_{i}\cdot\lambda_{i+1}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, the Fourier-transformed leaf amplitudes for gravitons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
At tree-level for configurations characterised by maximal helicity violation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is expressed as an integral over the moduli space of minitwistor lines
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 embedded in the non-singular quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 This interpretation arises from the fact that the integration with respect
 to the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{3}X$
\end_inset

 is localised by the weighted distributional forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{2h_{i}}$
\end_inset

, which impose the incidence relations characterising the curves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the support of the resulting integral is restricted to configuration
s where the graviton insertion points lie along such minitwistor lines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It must be emphasised that this integral does not represent a conventional
 volume over the moduli space of conic curves.
 The distributional forms 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{2h_{i}}$
\end_inset

 possess specific degrees of homogeneity that encode the celestial scaling
 dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the gravitons involved in the scattering process.
 It would be interesting to reformulate the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\text{m}}_{n}\left(\mathsf{Z}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 using the formalism proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "movshev2006berezinian"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "adamo2013moduli"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Generating Functional
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Generating-Functional-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now proceed to construct a generating functional for gravitational leaf
 superamplitudes by employing the geometric interpretation derived above.
 To incorporate the weight-shifting operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\fintop\,dh_{1}...dh_{n}$
\end_inset

, it is convenient to reformulate the amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Preliminaries: A Celestial Correlator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{O}\coloneqq\boldsymbol{O}[\omega^{A},\mathsf{P}_{i},\Psi_{\Delta_{i}}]$
\end_inset

 be an operator depending on the auxiliary spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}$
\end_inset

, the weight-shifting operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{P}_{i}$
\end_inset

, and the minitwistor graviton wavefunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\Delta_{i}}\left(\mathsf{Z}_{i};z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Define the expectation value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{O}$
\end_inset

 over the auxiliary spinor and the fermionic doublet 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{\chi},\boldsymbol{\chi}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \boldsymbol{O}\right\rangle _{\omega,n}\,=\,\underset{C_{n}}{\oint}\,\left\langle \omega d\omega\right\rangle \,\,\,\langle\omega\big|\,\boldsymbol{O}[\omega^{A},\mathsf{P}_{i},\Psi_{\Delta_{i}}]\,\big|\omega\rangle,\label{eq:}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $_{n}$
\end_inset

 denotes a small contour centred at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}$
\end_inset

, the insertion point of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th graviton on the celestial sphere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, introduce a sequence of Grassmann-valued scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{c}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,...,n$
\end_inset

, satisfying the normalisation condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{0|1}}{\int}d^{0|1}\mathsf{c}_{i}\,\left(\alpha_{i}+\mathsf{c}_{i}\beta_{i}\right)=\beta_{i},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i},\beta_{i}\in\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\coloneqq\Lambda[\mathsf{c}_{1},...,c_{n}]$
\end_inset

 the Grassmann algebra generated by the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{c}_{i}$
\end_inset

, which may be interpreted as 
\emph on
ghost-like fields
\emph default
 corresponding to anti-commuting spinless coordinates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}\left(\mathscr{H}_{c}\right)$
\end_inset

 be the ring of bounded linear operators on the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}_{c}$
\end_inset

 of celestial wavefunctions, and extend this structure to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

-graded ring:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{D}_{\Lambda}(\mathscr{H}_{c})\,\coloneqq\,\Lambda[\mathsf{c}]\otimes\mathcal{D}\left(\mathscr{H}_{c}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Using this formalism, the graviton vertex operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be unified into a single element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}_{\Lambda}\left(\mathscr{H}_{c}\right)$
\end_inset

 of the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}_{i}+\mathsf{c}_{i}\mathcal{V}_{i}\in\mathcal{D}_{\Lambda}\left(\mathscr{H}_{c}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With these constructions at hand, the gravitational leaf amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as the correlation function of the following operator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{M}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}}{\int}D^{3|16}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\,\,\,\left(\mathcal{U}_{i}+\mathsf{c}_{i}\mathcal{V}_{i}\right)\,\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2h_{i}}\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)\,K_{2h_{i}}\left(X;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\,\,\frac{1}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In terms of the correlator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \boldsymbol{O}\right\rangle _{\omega,n}$
\end_inset

 previously introduced in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:"

\end_inset

), the graviton leaf amplitude admits the following representation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\,=\,\left\langle \int d\mathsf{c}_{2}...d\mathsf{c}_{n-2}\,\,\,\boldsymbol{M}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)\right\rangle _{\omega,n}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Minitwistor Gravitational Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now proceed to construct the generating functional.
 The first step is to introduce the 
\emph on
minitwistor gravitational background potential
\emph default
 as a representative of a cohomology class:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\omega}_{i}\in\mathcal{D}_{\Lambda}[\mathscr{H}_{c}]\otimes\Omega^{0,1}\big(\mathbf{MT}^{2|8},\mathcal{O}(-2,-\Delta)\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Recall that the minitwistor superline 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)\subset\mathbf{MT}^{2|8}$
\end_inset

, associated with the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{X}^{\hat{I}}=\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

 in projective superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}$
\end_inset

, is define by the locus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)\,\coloneqq\,\left\{ \,\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\xi^{\alpha}\big)\in\mathbf{MT}^{2|4}\,\Big|\,\mu_{\dot{A}}=\lambda^{A}\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|},\,\xi^{\alpha}=\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\,\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In addition, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}$
\end_inset

 denote the restriction of the Dolbeault operator to the supercurve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We then define the 
\emph on
generating functional 
\emph default
as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\digamma[\boldsymbol{\omega}_{i}]\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}}{\int}D^{3|16}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\log\det\left(\overline{\partial}\,+\boldsymbol{\omega}_{i}\right)\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\digamma[\boldsymbol{\omega}_{i}]$
\end_inset

 generates 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{M}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 upon evaluation at the gravitational background potential:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\omega}_{i}\,=\,\underset{\mathcal{P}\times\mathbf{C}^{2}}{\int}\boldsymbol{\beta}_{i}\,\,\,\left(\mathcal{U}_{i}+\mathsf{c}_{i}\mathcal{V}_{i}\right)\,\boldsymbol{\psi}_{\Delta_{i}}\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)\,\mathcal{F}_{\Delta_{i}}\left(\lambda_{i},\mu_{i};z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right).\label{eq:-17}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\coloneqq1+i\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

 denotes the continuous principal series to which the celestial conformal
 weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{i}$
\end_inset

 belongs, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\Delta_{i}}\left(\lambda_{i},\mu_{i};z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the minitwistor representative defined in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-22"

\end_inset

).
 The volume form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\times\mathbf{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\beta}_{i}\,\coloneqq\,d\Delta_{i}\wedge dz_{i}\wedge d\bar{z}_{i}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To establish this claim, we expand the Quillen determinant as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\digamma[\boldsymbol{\omega}_{i}]\,=\,\sum_{m\geq2}\frac{\left(-1\right)^{m+1}}{m}\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}}{\int}D^{3|16}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\underset{\left(\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)\right)^{\times m}}{\int}\,\,\,\bigwedge_{i=1}^{m}\,D\lambda_{i}\,\,\,\boldsymbol{\omega}_{i}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,\,\,\frac{1}{\lambda_{i}\cdot\lambda_{i+1}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}_{i}$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-17"

\end_inset

) into the expansion yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\digamma[\boldsymbol{\omega}_{i}]\,\,\, & =\,\,\,\sum_{m\geq2}\,\,\,\frac{\left(-1\right)^{m+1}}{m}\,\,\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|16}}{\int}\,\,\,D^{3|16}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\underset{\left(\mathcal{P}\times\mathbf{C}^{2}\right)^{\times m}}{\int}\,\,\,\bigwedge_{i=1}^{m}\,\,\,\boldsymbol{\beta}_{i}\\
 & \,\left(\mathcal{U}_{i}+\mathsf{c}_{i}\mathcal{V}_{i}\right)\,\,\,\boldsymbol{\psi}_{2h_{i}}\left(z_{i}\cdot\theta^{\alpha}\right)\,K_{2h_{i}}\left(X;z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)\,\,\,\frac{1}{z_{i}\cdot z_{i+1}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

Finally, differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula $\digamma[\boldsymbol{\omega}_{i}]$
\end_inset

 with respect to the classical expectation values 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{h}_{2h_{i}}^{\ell_{i}}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 associated with the annihilation operator for a graviton with helicity
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{i}$
\end_inset

 and celestial scaling dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $2h_{i}$
\end_inset

, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta}{\delta\mathsf{h}_{2h_{1}}^{\ell_{1}}\left(z_{1},\bar{z}_{1}\right)}...\frac{\delta}{\delta\mathsf{h}_{2h_{n}}^{\ell_{n}}\left(z_{n},\bar{z}_{n}\right)}\,\digamma[\boldsymbol{\omega}_{i}]\,\Bigg|_{\boldsymbol{\psi}=0}=\boldsymbol{M}_{n}\left(z_{i},\bar{z}_{i},\Delta_{i}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

thus completing the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Minitwistor Celestial CFT
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Minitwistor-String-Theories"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation*
The integral operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\mathbf{CP}^{1}}\,$
\end_inset

 is understood to act on every term appearing on the right-hand side of
 an expression, irrespective of whether such terms are enclosed within brackets.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\mathbf{CP}^{1}}\,a+b\coloneqq\int_{\mathbf{CP}^{1}}\left(a+b\right).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation*
Local coordinates on minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 are denoted by 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}^{I}\coloneqq\big(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\big)$
\end_inset


\series default
, and to avoid unnecessary repetition, spinor indices in the arguments of
 functions (or functionals) will be shown only at the point of their initial
 definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Physical Motivation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Physical-Motivation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Twistor string theory
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "abou2008einstein,adamo2016twistor,geyer2014ambitwistor,geyer2015ambitwistor,geyer2022sagex,roiban2004googly,witten2004perturbative,Wolf:2006me"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 may be formulated as a theory of maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\big(Z^{I},\widetilde{Z}^{I}\big):\mathbf{CP}^{1}\longrightarrow\mathbf{PT}^{s}\times\mathbf{PT}^{s}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{Z}^{I}$
\end_inset

 denote holomorphic and anti-holomorphic fields, respectively, encoding
 the embedding of the Riemann sphere into supersymmetric projective twistor
 space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{PT}^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 The action functional is obtained by gauging the action of a holomorphic
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\gamma$
\end_inset

-system, where the gauging procedure implements the local rescaling symmetry
 of the 
\emph on
projective
\emph default
 geometry of twistor space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Explicitly, the action may be expressed as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{1}}{\int}d\sigma\,\,\,Y_{I}\overline{\nabla}Z^{I}+\widetilde{Y}_{I}\nabla\widetilde{Z}^{I}+...,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{Y}_{I}$
\end_inset

 are the canonical conjugate fields to 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{Z}^{I}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 The ellipsis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(...\right)$
\end_inset

 represents contributions from an auxiliary conformal matter system, which
 gives rises to worldsheet WZNW currents necessary for anomaly cancellation.
 The covariant derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla=\partial+\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nabla}=\overline{\partial}+\overline{\boldsymbol{a}}$
\end_inset

 are Dolbeault operators twisted by gauge fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\boldsymbol{a}}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the gauging of the rescaling symmetry of projective twistor
 space, under which the fields transform as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z^{I}\,\mapsto\,\alpha Z^{I},\,\,\,Y_{I}\,\mapsto\,\alpha^{-1}Y_{I},\,\,\,\overline{\boldsymbol{a}}\,\mapsto\,\overline{\boldsymbol{a}}\,-\,\overline{\partial}\,\log\alpha,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:\mathscr{U}\subseteq\mathbf{CP}^{1}\longrightarrow\mathbf{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is a nowhere vanishing holomorphic function, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}$
\end_inset

 the domain of a local trivialisation.
 Analogous transformations hold in the anti-holomorphic sector for 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{Z}^{I}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{Y}_{I}$
\end_inset

, and the gauge field 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We propose to follow a similar construction in our theory, with the goal
 of deriving equations of motion that describe the embedding of the celestial
 sphere into minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 as a minitwistor line.
 Unlike the anomaly-free twistor string theory described above, our theory
 will be defined only at the semiclassical level, due to the presence of
 quantum anomalies that preclude a full quantum formulation.
 In the semiclassical limit, we will demonstrate that the on-shell effective
 action reproduces the celestial leaf amplitudes associated with tree-level
 scattering processes for gluons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory and for gravitons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

, in configurations characterised by maximal helicity violation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Action Functional
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
First Step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the celestial sphere is modelled as the complex projective line.
 In addition, the minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 admits a holomorphic embedding of the Riemann sphere into minitwistor lines
 defined by the incidence relation.
 This embedding is formalised through the following sequence of constructions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\dot{A}}\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\right)$
\end_inset

 be a holomorphic map
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rigorously, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 is a section of the projective spinor bundle.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, possessing homogeneity of degree one with respect to the spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 and invariant under re-scalings of the ``spacetime'' coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}\in H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

, such that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{\dot{A}}\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\lambda^{A}\,\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The minitwistor line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the locus of points satisfying the incidence relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)\,\coloneqq\,\big\{\,\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)\in\mathbf{MT}\,\,\,\big|\,\,\,\mu_{\dot{A}}=F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\lambda\right)\,\big\}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Following the sheaf-theoretic conventions employed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "forster1981compact"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the restriction homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{X}\coloneqq\rho_{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}$
\end_inset

 associated with the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 acts on sections of the holomorphic vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(p,q\right)\longrightarrow\text{\textbf{MT}}$
\end_inset

 by mapping a representative 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 of a cohomology class as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{X}\left(g\right)\left(\lambda^{A}\right)\,\coloneqq\,g\left(\lambda^{A},F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\lambda\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, consider the canonical surjection 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{X}:\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

, which projects the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 onto the Riemann sphere.
 The natural embedding of the celestial sphere into the quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 (in the form of a minitwistor line) can be understood as a section of this
 fibration:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{X}:\mathbf{CP}^{1}\longrightarrow\mathcal{L}\left(X\right),\,\,\,\sigma_{X}\left(\lambda^{A}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\left(\lambda^{A},F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\lambda\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where, by construction, the composition satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{X}\circ\sigma_{X}=id_{\mathbf{CP}^{1}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, the holomorphic function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

, which 
\emph on
defines
\emph default
 the embedding of the Riemann sphere into the minitwistor space through
 the incidence relation, is 
\emph on
entirely
\emph default
 determined by its homogeneity properties and holomorphicity.
 Explicitly, it satisfies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\cdot\right)\in\Omega^{0,1}\left(X,\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)\right),\,\,\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\lambda\right)=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, by analogy with twistor string theory, one might be tempted to
 introduce an action integral over the Riemann sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

, in terms of the embedding function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

, as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{1}}{\int}D\lambda\,\,\,F_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,F^{\dot{A}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The corresponding equations of motion would yield the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\lambda\right)=0$
\end_inset

, which, as previously noted, completely determines the embedding map 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X}:\mathbf{CP}^{1}\longrightarrow\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the action integral written above is mathematically ill-defined
 due to a lack of projective invariance.
 Consider the integration measure 
\begin_inset Formula $D\lambda\coloneqq\varepsilon_{AB}\lambda^{A}d\lambda^{B}$
\end_inset

, which transforms under a rescaling 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}\mapsto\alpha\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $D\lambda\mapsto\alpha^{2}D\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Simultaneously, the ``kinetic term'' transforms as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,F^{\dot{A}}\mapsto\alpha^{2}F_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,F^{\dot{A}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus, the integrand 
\begin_inset Formula $D\lambda\,\,\,F_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,F^{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 fails to exhibit the required projective invariance under the transformation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}\mapsto\alpha\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

, precluding its interpretation as a meaningful action integral.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Second Step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our objective is to construct an action functional whose associated Euler-Lagran
ge equations precisely reproduce the embedding of the celestial sphere as
 a minitwistor line in  
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 A formulation of such an action can be introduced as follows
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A similar solution was formulated by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "adamo2021twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sharma2022twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "chiou2005massless"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For a mathematically rigorous discussion, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "samann2006aspects,samann2009mini"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dunajski2009twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "adamo2018minitwistors"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(\kappa_{1}^{A},\kappa_{2}^{A})$
\end_inset

 denote a normalised spinor basis satisfying the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{AB}\kappa_{1}^{A}\kappa_{2}^{B}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The conic curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 can be parametrised by trivialising the fibration 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{X}:\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 through the introduction of local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}$
\end_inset

, defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega^{A}\,\coloneqq\,\omega_{1}\kappa_{1}^{A}\,+\,\omega_{2}\,\kappa_{2}^{A}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}$
\end_inset

 are postulated to be projectively related to the minitwistor coordinates
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 through the relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda^{A}\,\equiv\,\frac{\omega^{A}}{\omega_{1}\omega_{2}}\,=\,\frac{\kappa_{1}^{A}}{\omega_{2}}\,+\,\frac{\kappa_{2}^{A}}{\omega_{1}}.\label{eq:-24}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Within this trivialisation, the holomorphic function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

, which determines the embedding map 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X}:\mathbf{CP}^{1}\longrightarrow\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

, yields a representative function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{\dot{A}}\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\omega^{A}\right)\,\,\,\coloneqq\,\,\,F_{\dot{A}}\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\lambda^{A}\left(\omega\right)\right)\,\,\,=\,\,\,\frac{\kappa_{1}^{A}}{\omega_{2}}\,\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}\,+\,\frac{\kappa_{2}^{A}}{\omega_{1}}\,\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two observations are now in order.
 First, the projective relation between 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}$
\end_inset

 guarantees that the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 can be inverted to recover 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, specifying 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 fully determines the embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X}:\mathbf{CP}^{1}\longrightarrow\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Second, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 is uniquely characterised as 
\emph on
the
\emph default
 solution to the following first-order partial differential equation
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}\left(z\right)\,\coloneqq\,\left(2\pi i\right)^{-1}\,\overline{\partial}\,z^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathbf{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,M_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\omega\right)\,=\,2\pi i\,\overline{\delta}\left(\omega_{2}\right)\,w_{1\dot{A}}+2\pi i\,\overline{\delta}\left(\omega_{1}\right)\,w_{2\dot{A}},\label{eq:-23}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the ``boundary conditions'' are specified by the residues at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, respectively, as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{1\dot{A}}\,=\,\kappa_{1}^{A}\,\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|},\,\,\,w_{2\dot{A}}\,=\,\kappa_{2}^{A}\,\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above discussion implies that, in seeking an action functional for a
 
\emph on
minitwistor celestial CFT
\emph default
, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 may be regarded as a dynamical variable whose Euler-Lagrange equations
 yield precisely the differential equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-23"

\end_inset

), while the boundary conditions are enforced through external source terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

, as opposed to its counterpart 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

, possesses an additional advantage due to its homogeneity properties in
 the trivialisation 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Specifically, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}$
\end_inset

, which renders the kinetic term:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,M^{\dot{A}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

suitably weighted for integration against the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $D\omega\coloneqq\varepsilon_{AB}\omega^{A}d\omega^{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, under a rescaling 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}\mapsto\alpha\omega^{A}$
\end_inset

, the measure transforms as 
\begin_inset Formula $D\omega\mapsto\alpha^{2}D\omega$
\end_inset

, while the kinetic term transforms as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,M^{\dot{A}}\,\mapsto\,\alpha^{-2}M_{\dot{A}}\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,M^{\dot{A}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

ensuring that the integrand:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D\omega\,\,\,M_{\dot{A}}\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,M^{\dot{A}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is weightless under such re-scalings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, we are naturally lead to consider the action functional:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{S}_{0}\big[M_{\dot{A}}(\omega^{A})\big]\,=\,\frac{1}{b}\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}{\int}\,D\omega\,\,\,M_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,M^{\dot{A}}\,+4\pi i\overline{\delta}\left(\omega_{2}\right)\left[w_{1}M\right]+4\pi i\overline{\delta}\left(\omega_{1}\right)\left[w_{2}M\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we have employed the spinor-helicity bracket notation to express the
 contraction of 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 with the external sources as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[w_{i}M\right]\coloneqq w_{i\dot{A}}M^{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

.
 Although the bracket notation is employed for the source terms, we refrain
 from using it in the kinetic term to avoid notational clutter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, a more suggestive rewriting of the action is possible by interpreting
 the sources 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

) as originating from an external current
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We follow the terminology of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "schwinger1966particles"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by defining:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{\dot{A}}\,\,\,\coloneqq\,\,\,4\pi i\,\overline{\delta}\left(\omega_{2}\right)\,\kappa_{1}^{A}\,\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}\,+\,4\pi i\,\overline{\delta}\left(\omega_{1}\right)\,\kappa_{2}^{A}\,\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}.\label{eq:-37}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The action functional then takes the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{S}_{0}=\,\frac{1}{b}\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)}{\int}\,D\omega\,\,\,M_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{X}\,M^{\dot{A}}\,+\,\left[JM\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $[JM]$
\end_inset

 denotes the contraction of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Supersymmetry
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Supersymmetry"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our extension of the RSVW formalism to celestial leaf amplitudes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity shows that the corresponding superamplitudes can be written
 as a Fourier transform on minitwistor superspace.
 This implies that any attempt to reproduce these amplitudes using a sigma
 model on the celestial sphere must include a supersymmetric version of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 as the target space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the subsequent subsections, we shall present an informal discussion of
 the minitwistor superspace, referring the reader to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rogers2007supermanifolds"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a rigorous mathematical treatment
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dewitt1992supermanifolds,leites1980introduction,manin1997introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Thereafter, we proceed to extend our construction of the sigma model action
 functional by formulating a generalisation in which the domain is the celestial
 
\emph on
supersphere
\emph default
 and the corresponding target space is taken to be the minitwistor 
\emph on
superspace
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Projective Superspace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by observing that the minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 is the space of oriented geodesics on the hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 A model for the hyperbolic geometry of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

 can be derived from the projective geometry of the three-dimensional real
 projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3}$
\end_inset

, as reviewed in the Appendix.
 Accordingly, our discussion of the minitwistor 
\emph on
superspace
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

 starts with a preliminary definition of supermanifold
\emph on
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3|2\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

.

\emph default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We identify the projective superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3|2\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

 with the trivial superbundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3}\times\mathbf{CP}^{0|2\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

, in which the three-dimensional real projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3}$
\end_inset

 serves as the base manifold and the fibre is parametrised by ``fermionic
 degrees of freedom.'' To be precise, the typical fibre is charted by the
 introduction of Grassmann-valued 
\emph on
homogeneous
\emph default
 spinorial coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{A}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, subject to an equivalence relation under projective rescaling by a nonzero
 complex scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\sim\alpha\theta_{A}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 The normalisation of the fermionic ``dimensions'' is imposed through a
 Berezin integral over the fibre, given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int d^{0|2}\theta\,\,\,\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\theta_{B}^{\alpha}\,=\,\varepsilon_{AB}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The natural orientation of the total space of the superbundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3|2\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

 is induced by the Berezin-de Witt volume superform, defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{3|2\mathcal{N}}\mathbb{X}\,\coloneqq\,\frac{D^{3}X}{\left|X\right|^{4}}\,\wedge\,d^{0|2\mathcal{N}}\theta.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Minitwistor Superspace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

 (associated with the hyperbolic geometry modelled on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3|2\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

) is constructed by extending the bosonic minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 through the inclusion of Grassmann-odd coordinates that encode the ``fermionic
 dimensions.'' More precisely, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

 as the trivial superbundle:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}\,\coloneqq\,\mathbf{MT}\times\mathbf{CP}^{0|\mathcal{N}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the base manifold is the bosonic minitwistor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

, and the typical fibre is charted by the Grassmann-odd 
\emph on
homogeneous
\emph default
 scalar coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\{1,...,\mathcal{N}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A bundle superchart on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

 is given by a local trivialisation 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathscr{U},\mathsf{Z}^{I})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}\subseteq\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

 denotes an open neighbourhood and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}^{I}:\mathscr{U}\longrightarrow U\times\mathbf{CP}^{0|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a local coordinate map.
 The image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}^{I}$
\end_inset

 is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset\mathbf{CP}^{1|0}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1|0}$
\end_inset

, and the coordinate functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}^{I}$
\end_inset

 decompose as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p\in\mathscr{U}\mapsto\mathsf{Z}^{I}\left(p\right)\coloneqq(\lambda^{A}\left(p\right),\mu_{\dot{A}}\left(p\right),\zeta^{\alpha}\left(p\right)).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The canonical orientation of the minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

 is specified by the Berezin-de Witt volume superform on the total space
 of the superbundle, and is defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{2|\mathcal{N}}\mathsf{Z}\,\coloneqq\,D\lambda\,\wedge\,D\mu\,\wedge\,d^{0|\mathcal{N}}\zeta.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Minitwistor Superlines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In minitwistor superspace, the minitwistor lines are generalised to 
\emph on
superlines
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, each associated with a ``spacetime'' point 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha})\in\mathbf{RP}^{3|2\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

.
 The incidence relation defining these supercurves is determined by sections
 of the 
\emph on
projective spinor superbundle
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{PS}_{3|2\mathcal{N}}\coloneqq\mathbf{RP}^{3|2\mathcal{N}}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1|0}$
\end_inset

, which are given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{\dot{A}}(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha};\lambda^{A})\,\coloneqq\,\lambda^{A}\,\frac{X_{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|},\,\,\,G^{\alpha}(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha};\lambda^{A})\,\coloneqq\,\lambda^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The supercurve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, which we shall refer to as the 
\emph on
minitwistor superline 
\emph default
based at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, is then defined as the locus of points in minitwistor superspace satisfying
 the incidence relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)\,\coloneqq\,\big\{\,\mathsf{Z}^{I}\,\in\,\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}\,\big|\,\mu_{\dot{A}}=F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right),\,\zeta^{\alpha}=G^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)\,\big\},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Z}^{I}=(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}},\zeta^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 denotes local coordinates on the minitwistor superspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To formalise the restriction of holomorphic sections to a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, let us consider a representative 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 of a cohomology class associated to the vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(p,q\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 The restriction homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}$
\end_inset

 maps this section to a section of the fibration 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 by evaluating it along the incidence relations defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\left(\lambda^{A}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\rho_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\left(g\right)\left(\lambda^{A}\right)\,\coloneqq g\left(\lambda^{A},F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right),G^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Embedding as a Section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider the canonical projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\left(X,\theta\right)}:\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 which maps each point on the supercurve to its projective coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $[\lambda^{A}]\in\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 A holomorphic embedding of the celestial sphere onto the minitwistor superline
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 can thus be identified with a section of this fibration.
 We denote this section by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\left(X,\theta\right)}:\mathbf{CP}^{1|0}\longrightarrow\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right),\,\,\,\sigma_{\left(X,\theta\right)}\left(\lambda^{A}\right)\coloneqq\left(\lambda^{A},F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right),G^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\left(X,\theta\right)}\circ\sigma_{\left(X,\theta\right)}=id_{\mathbf{CP}^{1}}$
\end_inset

 by construction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Construction of the Action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
First Step: Dynamical Variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To formulate a theory whose solutions to the equations of motion correspond
 to embeddings of the celestial sphere into minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

, it suffices to specify the holomorphic sections 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 introduced previously as dynamical variables.
 However, as observed, both 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 exhibit homogeneity of degree one in the spinor variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, any attempt to construct a weightless kinetic term using
 these functions directly would be inconsistent with the homogeneity degree
 of the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $D\lambda=\varepsilon_{AB}\lambda^{A}d\lambda^{B}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To resolve this issue, we employ the same procedure used in the bosonic
 case: we introduce a normalised spinor basis 
\begin_inset Formula $(\kappa_{1}^{A},\kappa_{2}^{A})$
\end_inset

 satisfying the normalisation condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{AB}\kappa_{1}^{A}\kappa_{2}^{B}=1$
\end_inset

, and we define a trivialisation of the fibration 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\left(X,\theta\right)}:\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 via a new spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}$
\end_inset

 expressed as a linear combination of the basis spinors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}\coloneqq\omega_{1}\kappa_{1}^{A}+\omega_{2}\kappa_{2}^{A}$
\end_inset

.
 We also postulate that the spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}$
\end_inset

 is projectively related to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 by Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-24"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step is to reformulate the section 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 in terms of this new spinor basis.
 Specifically, we define the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{\dot{A}}\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha};\omega^{A}\right)\,\coloneqq\,F_{\dot{A}}\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha};\omega^{A}\left(\lambda\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which contains the same information as 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 in terms of the new spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}$
\end_inset

.
 The properties of this function have already been analysed in our prior
 discussion on the bosonic model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now focus our attention on 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

, which we reformulate analogously as a new function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N^{\alpha}\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha};\omega^{A}\right)\,\coloneqq\,G^{\alpha}\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha};\omega^{A}\left(\lambda\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which can be rewritten as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\omega\right)\,=\,\frac{\widetilde{w}_{1}^{\alpha}}{\omega_{2}}\,+\,\frac{\widetilde{w}_{2}^{\alpha}}{\omega_{1}};\,\,\,\text{where}\,\,\,\widetilde{w}_{i}^{\alpha}\,\coloneqq\,\kappa_{i}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\,\left(i=1,2\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{A}$
\end_inset

 are projectively related, the above expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 can be inverted to recover 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 if the function 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 is given.
 Therefore, specifying the embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\left(X,\theta\right)}:\mathbf{CP}^{1}\longrightarrow\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 into a minitwistor superline is equivalent to specifying the pair of functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\dot{A}}\left(X,\theta;\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We thus arrive at the following conclusion: the set of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{M_{\dot{A}},N^{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

 can be taken as the dynamical fields in the supersymmetric generalisation
 of the minitwistor celestial CFT.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An additional remark is in order about the function 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It can be seem that this function is uniquely determined as 
\emph on
the
\emph default
 solution to the following partial differential equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,N^{\alpha}\left(X,\theta;\lambda\right)\,=\,2\pi i\,\overline{\delta}\left(\omega_{2}\right)\,\widetilde{w}_{1}^{\alpha}\,+\,2\pi i\,\overline{\delta}\left(\omega_{1}\right)\,\widetilde{w}_{2}^{\alpha},\label{eq:-38}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the boundary conditions are specified by the residues 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{w}_{1}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{w}_{2}$
\end_inset

 at the poles 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Second Step: Action Functional 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now arrive at the construction of an action that gives rise to a well-posed
 variational principle, whose associated Euler-Lagrange equations describe
 the embedding of the celestial sphere into minitwistor superspace as minitwisto
r supercurves.
 The proposed action is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{S}\,[M_{\dot{A}},N^{\alpha},e_{\alpha}]\,=\,\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}{\int}\,D\omega\,\,\,M_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,M^{\dot{A}}\,+\,e_{\alpha}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,N^{\alpha}\,+\,J_{\dot{A}}M^{\dot{A}}-e_{\alpha}K^{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The external bosonic current 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 appearing in the action is identical to the one introduced in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-37"

\end_inset

), while the newly introduced fermionic current 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K^{\alpha}\,\coloneqq\,2\pi i\,\overline{\delta}\left(\omega_{2}\right)\,\kappa_{1}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\,+\,2\pi i\,\overline{\delta}\left(\omega_{1}\right)\,\kappa_{2}^{A}\theta_{A}^{\alpha}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is a Lagrange multiplier, and that the equations of motion are given by
 Eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-23"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-38"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Celestial Supersphere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final level of abstraction is achieved through the extension of the
 celestial sphere to its 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 supersymmetric generalisation, the 
\emph on
celestial supersphere
\emph default
.
 This extension is obtained by adjoining to the homogeneous coordinates
 
\begin_inset Formula $[\omega^{A}]\in\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 two Grassmann-odd variables, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\eta}$
\end_inset

, which satisfy the Berezin normalisation condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\int d^{0|2}\eta\,\,\,\eta\bar{\eta}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The celestial supersphere is equipped with a natural orientation given
 by the Berezin-de Witt superform:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d^{1|2}z\,\coloneqq\,D\omega\,\wedge\,d^{0|2}\eta.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hereafter, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{L}}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 the minitwistor line obtained from the embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1|2}\longrightarrow\widetilde{\mathcal{L}}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To describe the local geometry of the celestial supersphere, we introduce
 a 
\emph on
super-vielbein 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\dot{A}}^{\,\,\,\alpha}$
\end_inset

 
\emph default
that satisfies the orthonormality condition 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\dot{A}}^{\,\,\,\alpha}E_{\,\,\,\beta}^{\dot{A}}=\delta_{\,\,\,\beta}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, note the following 
\emph on
algebraic 
\emph default
identities:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & M_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,M^{\dot{A}}+\,e_{\alpha}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,N^{\alpha}\\
 & =\int d^{0|2}\eta\,\,\,\big(\,\eta M_{\dot{A}}+\bar{\eta}E_{\dot{A}}^{\,\,\,\alpha}e_{\alpha}\,\big)\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,\big(\,\bar{\eta}M^{\dot{A}}-\eta E_{\,\,\,\beta}^{\dot{A}}N^{\beta}\,\big),
\end{align}

\end_inset

and:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & J_{\dot{A}}M^{\dot{A}}-e_{\alpha}K^{\alpha}\\
 & =\int d^{0|2}\eta\,\,\,\big(\,\eta J_{\dot{A}}+\bar{\eta}E_{\dot{A}}^{\,\,\,\alpha}e_{\alpha}\,\big)\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,\big(\,\bar{\eta}M^{\dot{A}}+\eta E_{\,\,\,\beta}^{\dot{A}}K^{\beta}\,\big).
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To facilitate a more compact notation, we define the 
\emph on
superfields:
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{\dot{A}}\left(\omega,\eta,\bar{\eta}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\eta M_{\dot{A}}+\bar{\eta}E_{\dot{A}}^{\,\,\,\alpha}e_{\alpha},\,\,\,Q^{\dot{A}}\left(\omega,\eta,\bar{\eta}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\bar{\eta}M^{\dot{A}}-\eta E_{\,\,\,\beta}^{\dot{A}}N^{\beta},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and introduce the 
\emph on
super-currents
\emph default
: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
j_{\dot{A}}\left(\omega,\eta,\bar{\eta}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\eta J_{\dot{A}}+\bar{\eta}E_{\dot{A}}^{\,\,\,\alpha}e_{\alpha},\,\,\,k^{\dot{A}}\left(\omega,\eta,\bar{\eta}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\bar{\eta}M^{\dot{A}}+\eta E_{\,\,\,\beta}^{\dot{A}}K^{\beta}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Finally, the action for the supersymmetric minitwistor celestial CFT can
 be expressed in terms of these superfields and super-currents as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{S}[P,Q,j,k]\,=\,\frac{1}{b}\underset{\widetilde{\mathcal{L}}\left(X,\theta\right)}{\int}d^{1|2}z\,\,\,P_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,Q^{\dot{A}}\,+\,[jk],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the bracket 
\begin_inset Formula $[jk]$
\end_inset

 denotes the spinor contraction of the super-currents 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Phenomenology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conventional superstring theory, phenomenological considerations arise
 from the study of Calabi-Yau compactifications or D-brane configurations.
 In twistor and ambitwistor string theories, such considerations are incorporate
d within an auxiliary conformal matter system, which we briefly discussed
 in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Physical-Motivation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The minitwistor celestial CFTs constructed in this work follow an analogous
 procedure: the relevant physical features are encoded in an auxiliary matter
 model, which we shall now proceed to define.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fermionic System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with the following physical motivations.
 First, the generating functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\digamma[\boldsymbol{\omega}]$
\end_inset

, derived in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Generating-Functional"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory and in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Generating-Functional-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity, is expressed as an integral over projective superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3|2\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

 of the Quillen determinant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

 be a gauge Lie group with Lie algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}\simeq\left(T_{e}\left(\mathbf{G}\right),[\cdot,\cdot]\right)$
\end_inset

, Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathsf{T}^{a}\}$
\end_inset

 a basis of generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 in the fundamental representation 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, satisfying the normalisation condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Tr}\left(\mathsf{T}^{a}\mathsf{T}^{b}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\boldsymbol{k}^{ab}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}^{ab}$
\end_inset

 denotes the Cartan-Killing form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

.
 The generators obey the commutation relations 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathsf{T}^{a},\mathsf{T}^{b}]=if^{abc}\mathsf{T}^{c}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{abc}$
\end_inset

 are the structure constants of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

-valued connection one-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}=\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}\mathsf{T}^{a}$
\end_inset

 on a principal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

-bundle over the Riemann sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q,\bar{q}\right)$
\end_inset

 denote a fermionic system defined on the associated vector bundle, whose
 typical fibre is isomorphic to the representation space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 The dynamics of the fermionic system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q,\bar{q}\right)$
\end_inset

 is governed by the action functional:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{S}_{(q,\bar{q})}\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathbf{CP}^{1}}{\int}d\sigma\,\,\,\bar{q}^{\text{i}}\left(\overline{\partial}+\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}\mathsf{T}_{\text{ij}}^{a}\right)q^{\text{j}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d\sigma$
\end_inset

 denotes the ``volume'' form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\partial}$
\end_inset

 is the Dolbeault operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, it is well-known
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "nair2005chern"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that the corresponding quantum effective action for this system is given
 by the chiral determinant of the associated Dirac operator (or twisted
 Dolbeault operator):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{W}_{(q,\bar{q})}\,\propto\,\mathsf{Tr}\log\left(\overline{\partial}+\boldsymbol{\omega}\right).\label{eq:-57}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Keeping these remarks in mind, we proceed by considering the principal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

-bundle over a minitwistor supercurve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, equipped with a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

-valued connection one-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}=\boldsymbol{\omega}^{a}\mathsf{T}^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Introduce the fermionic system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q,\bar{q}\right)$
\end_inset

 defined on the associated vector bundle over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, and define the superfields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi\left(\omega,\eta,\bar{\eta}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\bar{\eta}\,q,\,\,\,\bar{\psi}\left(\omega,\eta,\bar{\eta}\right)\,\coloneqq\,\eta\,\bar{q}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We propose that the 
\emph on
interaction term
\emph default
 in the action functional is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{S}_{int}\,\coloneqq\,\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}{\int}d^{1|2}z\,\,\,\bar{\psi}\left(\overline{\partial}+\boldsymbol{\omega}\right)\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,\psi.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore, the complete action describing the minitwistor celestial CFT
 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}\,=\,\,\frac{1}{b}\underset{\widetilde{\mathcal{L}}\left(X,\theta\right)}{\int}d^{1|2}z\,\,\,P_{\dot{A}}\,\overline{\partial}\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,Q^{\dot{A}}\,+\,[jk]\,+\,b\,\bar{\psi}\left(\overline{\partial}+\boldsymbol{\omega}\right)\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}\,\psi,\label{eq:-56}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 controls the semiclassical approximation, and is analogous to the Liouville
 coupling constant
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cf.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ribault2005h3+"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Semiclassical Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We turn now to the task of demonstrating that the semiclassical effective
 action arising from the theory described by Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-56"

\end_inset

) yields the generating functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\digamma[\boldsymbol{\omega}]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prior to presenting the path-integral formulation of the effective action,
 we recall the key observation made in the concluding remarks of Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:-Supersymmetric-Yang-Mills"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The dynamical fields in the present theory correspond to the embedding
 maps of the celestial sphere into minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

, realised as minitwistor superlines 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Formally, these embeddings are represented by sections:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\left(X,\theta\right)}:\mathbf{CP}^{1}\longrightarrow\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

of the canonical fibration:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{\left(X,\theta\right)}:\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{CP}^{1}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus, an integral such as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|2\mathcal{N}}}{\int}\,D^{3|2\mathcal{N}}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\underset{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}{\int}\,\,\,\left(...\right)\,\,\,,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

must be interpreted as an integral over the moduli space of 
\emph on
embeddings 
\emph default
of the celestial sphere into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

, rather than an integral over multiple distinct celestial spheres parametrised
 by coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{X}^{\hat{I}}=\left(X_{A\dot{A}},\theta_{A}^{\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

 in projective superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{RP}^{3|2\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is physically important, because semiclassically the path integral
 is not summing over disconnected celestial spheres but rather over all
 possible embeddings of a single celestial sphere as a minitwistor superline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, the semiclassical effective action 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{W}$
\end_inset

 must account for contributions from all possible embeddings of the celestial
 sphere into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

, and is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{W}\,=\,-\lim_{b\rightarrow0^{+}}b\,\,\,\log\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|2\mathcal{N}}}{\int}\,D^{3|2\mathcal{N}}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\int\left[dMdNd\psi d\bar{\psi}\right]\,\,\,\exp\left(-\mathcal{I}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the semiclassical limit 
\begin_inset Formula $b\rightarrow0^{+}$
\end_inset

, the dominant contribution to the path integral over the embedding fields
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 arises from the saddle-point approximation, which enforces the classical
 equations of motion, given by Eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-23"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-38"

\end_inset

), and are precisely those that define the embedding maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}\longrightarrow\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Accordingly, the path integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $b\rightarrow0^{+}$
\end_inset

 reduces to an evaluation of the remaining terms in the action at the locus
 defined by the incidence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, which is achieved by the application of the restriction homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having restricted the bosonic path integral to the moduli space of embeddings
 of the celestial sphere, we now consider the fermionic contributions.
 The path integral over the fermionic system 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi,\bar{\psi})$
\end_inset

 results in the chiral determinant, which, as shown in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-38"

\end_inset

), is the supersymmetric extension of the Quillen determinant.
 Consequently, the semiclassical effective action 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{W}$
\end_inset

 becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{W}\,=\,\underset{\mathbf{RP}^{3|2\mathcal{N}}}{\int}\,D^{3|2\mathcal{N}}\mathbb{X}\,\,\,\log\det\left(\overline{\partial}+\boldsymbol{\omega}\right)\,\big|_{\mathcal{L}\left(X,\theta\right)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above expression recovers the minitwistor generating functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\digamma[\boldsymbol{\omega}]$
\end_inset

 for the background potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset

 appropriate to the spacetime theory under consideration.
 This demonstrates that the minitwistor sigma model reproduces semiclassically
 the tree-level MHV celestial leaf superamplitudes for gluons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory and for gravitons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Discussion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The supersymmetric minitwistor celestial CFTs developed in the previous
 section reproduce the tree-level celestial leaf superamplitudes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=4$
\end_inset

 SYM theory and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=8$
\end_inset

 Supergravity for MHV configurations.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "banerjee2021mhv"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposed that the MHV sector of celestial CFT might serve as a minimal
 model for celestial holography.
 The minitwistor celestial CFTs introduced here could contribute to addressing
 this conjecture for the following reason.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formalism presented in this paper relies on minitwistor wavefunctions,
 defined as cohomology classes in minitwistor space.
 This approach extends the RSVW prescription to celestial amplitudes and
 offers a new perspective on the celestial leaf amplitudes.
 In this setup, tree-level MHV leaf amplitudes are expressed as integrals
 over the moduli space of minitwistor lines.
 It is therefore reasonable to suggest that celestial amplitudes corresponding
 to next-to-MHV (NMHV) configurations could be described by integrals over
 the moduli space of higher-degree curves in minitwistor space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We propose that future work should focus on extending the minitwistor generating
 functional developed here to systematically incorporate NMHV celestial
 amplitudes.
 Additionally, it would be worthwhile to study a celestial version of the
 Cachazo-Svrcek-Witten (CSW) expansion for leaf amplitudes.
 We expect that such an extension could offer a concrete path toward proving
 the Banerjee-Gosh conjecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integral over the moduli space of special curves in minitwistor superspace
 that arises from our extension of the RSVW formalism to celestial amplitudes
 is not a standard volume integral.
 This is because the delta functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\delta}_{\Delta_{i}}$
\end_inset

, which localise the superspace integral to the locus of incidence in minitwisto
r space, have non-trivial homogeneity properties given by the celestial
 conformal weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 It would be interesting to reformulate these integrals using the formalism
 introduced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "movshev2006berezinian"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and further elaborated by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "adamo2013moduli"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the semiclassical limit 
\begin_inset Formula $b\rightarrow0^{+}$
\end_inset

 of our minitwistor celestial CFTs, where the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 plays a role similar to the Liouville coupling constant, we have been able
 to reproduce celestial amplitudes at tree level.
 An important direction for future research is to explore whether extending
 beyond the semiclassical limit could produce loop corrections, similar
 to those studied in the context of celestial Liouville theory in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mol2024partial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Another promising approach would be to consider a complex scaling reduction
 of Berkovits' original twistor string theory to minitwistor space.
 Investigating whether the resulting minitwistor string theory can generate
 NMHV celestial leaf amplitudes as integrals over the moduli space of higher-deg
ree algebraic curves in minitwistor superspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}^{2|\mathcal{N}}$
\end_inset

 would be an important step forward.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\start_of_appendix
Minitwistor Geometry
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Minitwistor-Geometry"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-singular quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}\subset\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

 upon which our celestial CFTs will be defined corresponds to the minitwistor
 space associated with the hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, we shall succinctly review how the hyperbolic geometry of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 arises from the projective geometry of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we recapitulate the Hitchin construction
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As developed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hitchin1982twistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of minitwistor space, and discuss the mapping from representatives of cohomolog
y classes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 to conformal primaries of the 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

-WZNW model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we follow the notation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kobayashi1996foundations"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Note.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The present subsection adopts a more mathematical style compared to the
 remainder of this manuscript, and it is intended to acquaint the reader
 with basic notions of minitwistor geometry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hyperbolic Space from Projective Geometry
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Hyperbolic-Space-from"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the four-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 be homogeneous coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

, subject to the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}\sim a\cdot X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is any non-zero complex scalar.
 A necessary and sufficient condition for a set of components of a holomorphic
 metric (given in the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

) to be well-defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

, is that such components must be invariant under the ``gauge transformations''
 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}\mapsto a\cdot X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\in\mathbf{C}^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

, and they must not possess any components along the scaling dimension defined
 by this equivalence relation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A first fundamental form satisfying these conditions is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ds^{2}=-\frac{dX^{2}}{X^{2}}+\left(\frac{X\cdot dX}{X^{2}}\right)^{2}.\label{eq:-21}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The invariance of 
\begin_inset Formula $ds^{2}$
\end_inset

 under rescalings is manifest.
 Introducing the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

 associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $ds^{2}$
\end_inset

, for which 
\begin_inset Formula $ds^{2}=\boldsymbol{g}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}dX^{A\dot{A}}\otimes dX^{B\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

, we observe that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{£}_{\Upsilon}\boldsymbol{g}=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Upsilon\coloneqq X^{A\dot{A}}\frac{\partial}{\partial X^{A\dot{A}}}\in\mathscr{X}\left(\mathbf{CP}^{3}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the Euler vector field, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{£}_{\Upsilon}$
\end_inset

 is the Lie derivative along the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Upsilon$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, 
\begin_inset Formula $ds^{2}$
\end_inset

 is devoid of components along the scaling dimension, and defines a first
 fundamental form on the open submanifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}-\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 denotes the closed submanifold on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

 becomes singular, and is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{B}\coloneqq\left\{ \left(X^{A\dot{A}}\right)\in\mathbf{CP}^{3}\,\big|\,\left\langle X,X\right\rangle =0\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Rewriting 
\begin_inset Formula $ds^{2}$
\end_inset

 in terms of normalised coordinates, 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}/\left|X\right|$
\end_inset

, we find:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ds^{2}=-\varepsilon_{A\dot{A}}\varepsilon_{B\dot{B}}d\left(\frac{X^{A\dot{A}}}{\left|X\right|}\right)d\left(\frac{X^{B\dot{B}}}{\left|X\right|}\right),\,\,\,\left|X\right|^{2}\coloneqq\left\langle X,X\right\rangle .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It follows that the submanifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}-\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

, endowed with the geometry induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}_{A\dot{A}B\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

, is isometric to complexified 
\begin_inset Formula $AdS_{3}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}\simeq\partial AdS_{3}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to its conformal boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain either the Kleinian hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 or the Lorentzian 
\begin_inset Formula $AdS_{3}$
\end_inset

, we restrict the metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}_{AB\dot{A}\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

 to an appropriate slice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This is achieved by imposing suitable reality conditions on the components
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minitwistor Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A minitwistor space
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hitchin1982monopoles"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jones1985minitwistor"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is defined as any two-dimensional complex manifold containing a rational
 curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 (a holomorphic embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

) with a normal bundle isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Any such curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 is referred to as a 
\emph on
minitwistor line 
\emph default
or a 
\emph on
Hitchin special curve
\emph default
.
 By virtue of a theorem due to Kodaira
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cf.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kodaira1963structure"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kobayashi1996foundations"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 admits a three-parameter family 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 of such special curves.
 Denoting the corresponding parameter space by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}\left(\mathscr{F}\right)$
\end_inset

, a corollary of Kodaira's theorem establishes the existence of an isomorphism
 between the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{x}\big(\mathbf{W}\left(\mathscr{F}\right)\big)$
\end_inset

, at any point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{W}\left(\mathscr{F}\right)$
\end_inset

, and the space of globally defined smooth sections of the normal bundle
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}_{x}$
\end_inset

 of the Hitchin special curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}_{x}\subset\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left(\mathscr{C}_{x},\mathcal{N}_{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, it has been demonstrated by Hitchin (1982) that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}\coloneqq\mathbf{W}\left(\mathscr{F}\right)$
\end_inset

, constructed in this manner, can be endowed with the structure of a Weyl
 manifold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our purposes, we specialise to the non-singular quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\coloneqq\mathbf{CP}^{1}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)$
\end_inset

 denote homogeneous coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}\times\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 is realised as an embedding into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

 through the mapping:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)\in\text{\textbf{MT}}\mapsto[\lambda^{A}\mu_{\dot{A}}]\in\mathbf{CP}^{3}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For any point 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}\in\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

, the locus of incidence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)\coloneqq\left\{ \left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)\in\mathbf{MT}\,\big|\,\mu_{\dot{A}}=\lambda^{A}X_{A\dot{A}}\right\} ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

defines a conic contained within 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 This conic satisfies the following property: there exists a hyperplane
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}\subset\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(X\right)=\mathbf{MT}\cap\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Any such conics intersect in precisely two points.
 As a consequence, these conics have a normal bundle isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 and thus constitute special curves in the sense of Hitchin.
 Moreover, the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\big(X^{A\dot{A}}\big)=0$
\end_inset

 is both necessary and sufficient for a plane section to be tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 Any such plane section determines 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 up to a proportionality factor.
 Accordingly, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}$
\end_inset

 of plane sections that are not tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 may be identified with the set of non-null rays emanating from the origin
 in Minkowski space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{\left(1,3\right)}$
\end_inset

, thereby realising 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}$
\end_inset

 as a hyperboloid embedded into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{\left(1,3\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider two points 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}},Y^{A\dot{A}}\in\mathbf{W}$
\end_inset

 that are null-separated in the Weyl conformal structure.
 In this case, either the corresponding conics in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 intersect, or the associated planes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

 intersect along a line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 that is tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, there exists a unique plane passing through 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 and tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that the algebraic equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det\big(X^{A\dot{A}}+tY^{A\dot{A}}\big)=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

admits solutions with multiplicity greater than one.
 By restricting 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 to be unit vectors in Minkowski space and expanding the preceding equation
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 are null-separated in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}$
\end_inset

 if and only if:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X^{A\dot{A}}Y_{A\dot{A}}=\varepsilon_{A\dot{A}}\varepsilon_{B\dot{B}}X^{A\dot{A}}Y^{B\dot{B}}=1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

However, it is well known that the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 between the points 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 in the first fundamental form induced on the hyperboloid
\series bold
 
\series default
is given by
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\cosh^{-1}\big(X^{A\dot{A}}Y_{A\dot{A}}\big)$
\end_inset

.
 
\series default
Thus, the conformal metric associated with Hitchin's construction is equivalent
 to the class of metrics conformally related to the standard hyperbolic
 metric on 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now establish that the Weyl conformal structure determined via the Hitchin
 correspondence from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the conformal structure obtained from the hyperboloid
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

, modulo conformal rescalings of the metric; consequently, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 are conformally related.
 In fact, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}},Y^{A\dot{A}}\in\mathbf{W}$
\end_inset

 be two points, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{X},\Pi_{Y}\subset\mathbf{CP}^{3}$
\end_inset

 denote the planes corresponding to these points.
 Consider the line of intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\coloneqq\Pi_{X}\cap\Pi_{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 denote the one-parameter family of planes passing through 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
 The family 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 defines a set of conics contained within 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 that intersect at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 and defines a Weyl geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}$
\end_inset

.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is precisely the intersection of the hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 with the two-dimensional subspace spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 in Minkowski space.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 is endowed with a hyperbolic metric, the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a geodesic of the metric induced on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes the equivalence of the conformal structure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}$
\end_inset

 with that on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

, thereby completing the proof that the non-singular quadric 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 is the minitwistor space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 via the Hitchin correspondence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Holomorphic Vector Bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(p,q\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-Holomorphic-Vector"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection, we shall define the holomorphic vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(p,q\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

 which serves as the domain upon which the minitwistor Penrose transform
 is defined.
 We establish that this bundle can be identified with the infinite-dimensional
 function space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}_{p,q}^{\infty}\left(\mathbf{MT}\right)$
\end_inset

, consisting of smooth complex-valued functions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h:\left(\mathbf{C}^{*}\right)^{2}\times\left(\mathbf{C}^{*}\right)^{2}\longrightarrow\mathbf{C},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

satisfying the homogeneity property:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h\left(a\cdot\lambda^{A},b\cdot\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)=a^{p}b^{q}\,\,\,h\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for every pair of nonzero complex scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the space of dotted two-component spinors forms a holomorphic
 vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)\oplus\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 fibered over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\mathscr{U}}\coloneqq\left(\mathscr{U},\vec{\mu}\right)$
\end_inset

 denote a local trivialisation of this bundle, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{U}\subset\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is an open neighbourhood and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\mu}:\mathscr{U}\longrightarrow\mathbf{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a coordinate map, which associates each dotted spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 with its coordinate representation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mu\right)_{\mathscr{U}}\coloneqq\left(\mu_{\dot{1}},\mu_{\dot{2}}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Similarly, the space of undotted two-component spinors can be described
 by a corresponding holomorphic vector bundle.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\mathscr{V}}\coloneqq(\mathscr{V},\vec{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 be an analogous local trivialisation, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{V}$
\end_inset

 is an open neighbourhood, and the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\lambda}:\mathscr{V}\longrightarrow\mathbf{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 assigns each undotted spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{A}$
\end_inset

 to its coordinate representation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{\mathscr{V}}\coloneqq(\lambda^{1},\lambda^{2}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Next, define the set:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}\,\coloneqq\,\big\{\,\big(\vec{\lambda},\vec{\mu},s\big)\,\big|\,\vec{\lambda}\in\left(\mathbf{C}^{*}\right)^{2},\,\vec{\mu}\in\left(\mathbf{C}^{*}\right),\,s\in\mathbf{C}\,\big\},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and introduce an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\simeq}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 as follows.
 For any pair of nonzero complex scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbf{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

, we impose the condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\big(\vec{\lambda},\vec{\mu},s\big)\,\boldsymbol{\simeq}\,\big(a\cdot\vec{\lambda},\,b\cdot\vec{\mu},\,\,\,a^{p}b^{q}\,\cdot\,s\big).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Taking the quotient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\simeq}$
\end_inset

 yields a new manifold,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{O}\left(p,q\right)\coloneqq\mathcal{P}/\boldsymbol{\simeq},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is endowed with the quotient topology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To establish the vector bundle structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(p,q\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

, consider the following diagram:
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation} 
\backslash
label{triangle-diagram} 
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[row sep=large, column sep=large] 
\backslash
mathbf{C}^{2} 
\backslash
times 
\backslash
mathbf{C}^{2} 
\backslash
arrow[dr, "
\backslash
pi"', font=
\backslash
Large] & & 
\backslash
mathcal{O}(p,q) 
\backslash
arrow[dl, "
\backslash
mathcal{Q}", font=
\backslash
Large] 
\backslash

\backslash
 & 
\backslash
mathbf{MT} & 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

with the mappings in the diagram defined as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi(\vec{\lambda},\vec{\mu})\coloneqq([\lambda^{A}],[\mu_{\dot{A}}]),\,\,\,\mathcal{Q}(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}})\coloneqq\pi(\vec{\lambda},\vec{\mu}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Consequently, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}$
\end_inset

 is a surjection with fibres isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

, and the transition functions between local trivialisations satisfy the
 holomorphic cocycle condition, thereby showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}$
\end_inset

 defines a holomorphic bundle over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\SpecialChar ligaturebreak

\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Proposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}_{p,q}^{\infty}\left(\mathbf{MT}\right)$
\end_inset

 denote the space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 complex-valued functions 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{C}^{*}\right)^{2}\times\left(\mathbf{C}^{*}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the homogeneity property:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h\left(a\cdot\lambda^{A},b\cdot\mu_{\dot{A}}\right)=a^{p}b^{q}\,\,\,h\left(\lambda^{A},\mu_{\dot{A}}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for every pair of nonzero complex scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 The function space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}_{p,q}^{\infty}\left(\mathbf{MT}\right)$
\end_inset

 can be canonically identified with the module 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{\infty}(\mathcal{O}(p,q))$
\end_inset

 of smooth sections on the holomorphic vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(p,q\right)\longrightarrow\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathscr{C}_{p,q}^{\infty}\left(\mathbf{MT}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For each minitwistor 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathsf{Z}}^{I}\coloneqq(\widetilde{\lambda}^{A},\widetilde{\mu}_{\dot{A}})\in\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

, define the set:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\digamma\coloneqq\left\{ \left(Z,h\left(Z\right)\right)\,\big|\,Z=(\vec{\lambda},\vec{\mu})\in\mathbf{C}^{2}\times\mathbf{C}^{2},\,\mathcal{\pi}\left(Z\right)=\widetilde{\mathsf{Z}}^{I}\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By the homogeneity condition satisfied by 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\digamma$
\end_inset

 consists of equivalence classes under 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\simeq}$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, this set determines a unique point 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\widetilde{\mathsf{Z}}^{I})$
\end_inset

 in the fibre of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(p,q\right)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathsf{Z}}^{I}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 defines a section 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathsf{Z}}^{I}\mapsto\sigma(\widetilde{\mathsf{Z}}^{I})$
\end_inset

 contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{\infty}(\mathcal{O}(p,q))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\Gamma^{\infty}(\mathcal{O}(p,q))$
\end_inset

 is a smooth section.
 For each minitwistor 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathsf{Z}}^{I}\in\mathbf{MT}$
\end_inset

, there exists a class 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{C}=\{(Z,s)\}$
\end_inset

 of equivalent pairs such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(Z)=\widetilde{\mathsf{Z}}^{I}$
\end_inset

.
 Choosing a representative 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=(\vec{\lambda},\vec{\mu})\in\mathbf{C}^{2}\times\mathbf{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

, we find a unique pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,s)\in\mathsf{C}$
\end_inset

 in the class.
 The section 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 therefore determines a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathscr{C}_{p,q}^{\infty}\left(\mathbf{MT}\right)$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\mapsto f\left(Z\right)\coloneqq s$
\end_inset

, which satisfies the homogeneity property by construction.
 Hence, the spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}_{p,q}^{\infty}\left(\mathbf{MT}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{\infty}(\mathcal{O}(p,q))$
\end_inset

 are isomorphic, as claimed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Leaf Amplitudes Review
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Leaf-Amplitudes-Review"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Klein Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
leaf representation
\emph default
 of celestial amplitudes is our main motivation for introducing multi-gluon
 and multi-graviton wavefunctions using minitwistor variables.
 This formalism requires the analytic continuation of Minkowski spacetime
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{\left(1,3\right)}$
\end_inset

 from a Lorentzian 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-+++\right)$
\end_inset

 to a Kleinian 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(--++\right)$
\end_inset

 signature.
 For this purpose, we briefly review the relevant aspects of Kleinian geometry,
 which have been investigated in detail by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barrett1994kleinian"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bhattacharjee2022celestial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "crawley2022black"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "cheung2003families"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "duary2024spectral"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by considering Cartesian coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(0\le\mu,\nu,...\leq3)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

, and define the Kleinian metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h_{\mu\nu}\coloneqq\text{diag}\left(-1,-1,+1,+1\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The resulting vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{\left(2,2\right)}\coloneqq\left(\mathbf{R}^{4},\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset

, equipped with the inner product:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle X,Y\right\rangle \coloneqq h_{\mu\nu}X^{\mu}Y^{\nu},\,\,\,\text{for}\,X^{\mu},Y^{\mu}\in\mathbf{R}^{\left(2,2\right)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is known as the 
\emph on
four-dimensional Klein space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We identify three distinguished submanifolds contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{\left(2,2\right)}$
\end_inset

: the 
\emph on
null cone
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

, the 
\emph on
time-like wedge
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{-}$
\end_inset

, and the 
\emph on
space-like wedge 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{+}$
\end_inset


\emph default
, defined (respectively) as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \Lambda\coloneqq\{\left(X^{\mu}\right)\in\mathbf{R}^{\left(2,2\right)}\,\big|\,\left\langle X,X\right\rangle =0\},\\
 & \mathbf{W}^{-}\coloneqq\{\left(X^{\mu}\right)\in\mathbf{R}^{\left(2,2\right)}\,\big|\,\left\langle X,X\right\rangle <0\},\\
 & \mathbf{W}^{+}\coloneqq\{\left(X^{\mu}\right)\in\mathbf{R}^{\left(2,2\right)}\,\big|\,\left\langle X,X\right\rangle >0\}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Time-like Wedge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To chart the time-like wedge 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{-}$
\end_inset

, we employ the coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{-}^{\mu}:\mathbf{W}^{-}\longrightarrow\mathbf{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

, defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & X_{-}^{0}\coloneqq\tau\cos\left(\psi\right)\cosh\left(\rho\right),\,\,\,X_{-}^{1}\coloneqq\tau\sin\left(\psi\right)\cosh\left(\rho\right),\\
 & X_{-}^{2}\coloneqq\tau\cos\left(\varphi\right)\sinh\left(\rho\right),\,\,\,X_{-}^{3}\coloneqq\tau\sin\left(\varphi\right)\sinh\left(\rho\right),
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,\rho\in\left(0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\psi,\varphi\right)\in S^{1}\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With respect to this parametrisation, the induced first fundamental form
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{-}$
\end_inset

 takes the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(ds^{2}\right)_{\mathbf{W}^{-}}=-d\tau^{2}+\tau^{2}\left(d\rho^{2}-\cosh^{2}\left(\rho\right)d\psi^{2}+\sinh^{2}\left(\rho\right)d\phi^{2}\right).\label{eq:-26}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It follows that the hypersurfaces of constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{-}$
\end_inset

 are diffeomorphic to the three-dimensional Lorentzian anti-de Sitter space
 with periodic time, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $AdS_{3}/\mathbf{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, the integration measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{-}$
\end_inset

 in the coordinate chart 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{-}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is given by the volume form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(d^{4}X\right){}_{\mathbf{W}^{-}}\coloneqq\frac{1}{2}\tau^{3}\sinh\left(2\rho\right)d\tau d\rho d\psi d\varphi,\label{eq:-27}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the juxtaposition of differentials is understood as the exterior product
 of differential forms, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tau d\rho d\psi d\varphi=d\tau\wedge d\rho\wedge d\psi\wedge d\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A closed submanifold of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{-}$
\end_inset

, which plays a central role in the subsequent discussion, is the 
\emph on
standard Kleinian hyperboloid 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset


\emph default
, defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{H}_{3}\coloneqq\{\left(X^{\mu}\right)\in\mathbf{R}^{\left(2,2\right)}\,\big|\,\left\langle X,X\right\rangle =-1\}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We chart 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 using the coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}:\mathbf{H}_{3}\longrightarrow\mathbf{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

, given by the functions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & x^{0}\coloneqq\cos\left(\psi\right)\cosh\left(\rho\right),\,\,\,x^{1}\coloneqq\sin\left(\psi\right)\cosh\left(\rho\right),\\
 & x^{2}\coloneqq\cos\left(\varphi\right)\sinh\left(\rho\right),\,\,\,x^{3}\coloneqq\sin\left(\varphi\right)\sinh\left(\rho\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The restriction of the first fundamental form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{-}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

, obtained via the pull-back 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{-}^{*}$
\end_inset

 of the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{-}:\mathbf{H}_{3}\longrightarrow\mathbf{W}^{-}$
\end_inset

, endows 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 with a Lorentzian metric.
 This structure implies the existence of an isometry from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $AdS_{3}/\mathbf{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding integration measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 is given by the volume form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d^{3}x\coloneqq\frac{1}{2}\sinh\left(2\rho\right)d\rho d\psi d\varphi.\label{eq:-28}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Combining Eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-27"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-28"

\end_inset

) for the volume forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{-}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

, respectively, we deduce:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(d^{4}X\right){}_{\mathbf{W}^{-}}=\tau^{3}d\tau d^{3}x.\label{eq:-33}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Space-like Wedge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The space-like wedge 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{+}$
\end_inset

 is parametrised by the coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{+}^{\mu}:\mathbf{W}^{+}\longrightarrow\mathbf{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

, defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{+}^{0}\coloneqq\tau\cos\left(\psi\right)\sinh\left(\rho\right),\,\,\,X_{+}^{1}\coloneqq\tau\sin\left(\psi\right)\sinh\left(\rho\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{+}^{2}\coloneqq\tau\cos\left(\varphi\right)\cosh\left(\rho\right),\,\,\,X_{+}^{3}\coloneqq\tau\sin\left(\varphi\right)\cosh\left(\rho\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first fundamental form induced on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{+}$
\end_inset

 from the Kleinian metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(ds^{2}\right)_{\mathbf{W}^{+}}=d\tau^{2}-\tau^{2}\left(d\rho^{2}+\sinh^{2}\left(\rho\right)d\psi^{2}-\cosh^{2}\left(\rho\right)d\varphi^{2}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The integration measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{+}$
\end_inset

 is represented by the volume form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(d^{4}X\right)_{\mathbf{W}^{+}}=-\frac{1}{2}\tau^{3}\sinh\left(2\rho\right)d\tau d\rho d\psi d\varphi.\label{eq:-29}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{+}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
unit hyperboloid 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}^{+}\coloneqq\{X_{+}^{\mu}\in\mathbf{R}^{(2,2)}\,\big|\,\left\langle X_{+},X_{+}\right\rangle =1\}$
\end_inset

, which is charted by the coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\mu}:\mathbf{H}_{3}^{+}\longrightarrow\mathbf{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 defined by the functions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y^{0}\coloneqq\cos\left(\psi\right)\sinh\left(\rho\right),\,\,\,y^{1}=\sin\left(\psi\right)\sinh\left(\rho\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y^{2}\coloneqq\cos\left(\varphi\right)\cosh\left(\rho\right),\,\,\,y^{3}\coloneqq\sin\left(\varphi\right)\cosh\left(\rho\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first fundamental form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

, induced by the pull-back of the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{+}:\mathbf{H}_{3}^{+}\longrightarrow\mathbf{W}^{+}$
\end_inset

, is given in these coordinates by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(ds^{2}\right)_{\mathbf{H}_{3}^{+}}=d\rho^{2}+\sinh^{2}\left(\rho\right)d\psi^{2}-\cosh^{2}\left(\rho\right)d\varphi^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The geometric distinction between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

 (from the time-like wedge) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

 lies in the interchange of the time-like and space-like orientations.
 Despite this difference, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

 remains diffeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $AdS_{3}/\mathbf{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 The volume form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

 is expressed as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d^{3}y=-\frac{1}{2}\sinh\left(2\rho\right)d\rho d\psi d\varphi.\label{eq:-30}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Finally, from Eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-29"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-30"

\end_inset

), we deduce the following decomposition of the integration measure:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(d^{4}X\right)_{\mathbf{W}^{+}}=\tau^{3}d^{3}y.\label{eq:-34}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spinor Algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Employing the Van der Waerden formalism, as reviewed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "veblen1933geometry"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "penrose1984spinors"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the inner product of two undotted two-component spinors, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{A}$
\end_inset

, is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \mu\nu\right\rangle \coloneqq\mu\cdot\nu\coloneqq\varepsilon_{AB}\mu^{A}\nu^{B}=\mu^{A}\nu_{A},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{AB}$
\end_inset

 is the Levi-Civita symbol, antisymmetric under index exchange, and normalised
 according to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{12}=-\varepsilon_{21}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The lowering and raising of spinor indices adhere to the standard convention,
 according to which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{A}\coloneqq\varepsilon_{AB}\mu^{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{A}=\varepsilon^{AB}\nu_{B}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{AB}$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{AC}\varepsilon_{CB}=\delta_{\,\,\,B}^{A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the inner product of two dotted spinors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

, is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[\bar{\mu}\bar{\nu}]\coloneqq\varepsilon^{\dot{A}\dot{B}}\bar{\mu}_{\dot{A}}\bar{\nu}_{\dot{B}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{\dot{A}\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

 is the antisymmetric Levi-Civita symbol for the dotted spinor space.
 Index manipulation for dotted spinors follows analogous rules, employing
 the conventions 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}^{\dot{A}}\coloneqq\varepsilon^{\dot{A}\dot{B}}\bar{\mu}_{\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}_{\dot{A}}\coloneqq\varepsilon_{\dot{A}\dot{B}}\bar{\nu}^{\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{\dot{A}\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{\dot{A}\dot{C}}\varepsilon^{\dot{C}\dot{B}}=\delta_{\dot{A}}^{\,\,\,\dot{B}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
Kleinian Pauli matrices
\emph default
, which establish a correspondence between vector and spinor indices in
 Kleinian signature, are defined as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\sigma}^{0}=\sigma^{3},\,\,\,\boldsymbol{\sigma}^{1}=\sigma^{1},\,\,\,\boldsymbol{\sigma}^{2}=\mathbb{I},\,\,\,\boldsymbol{\sigma}^{3}=i\sigma^{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma^{\mu})_{A\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 denotes the Lorentzian Pauli matrices, defined in the 
\begin_inset Formula $(-+++)$
\end_inset

 signature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason for this choice becomes apparent through the following construction.
 Consider the map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{\left(2,2\right)}$
\end_inset

 into the space of real 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices, given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X^{\mu}\mapsto(\underline{X})_{A\dot{A}}\coloneqq\sum_{\mu=0}^{3}X^{\mu}(\boldsymbol{\sigma}^{\mu})_{A\dot{A}}=\begin{pmatrix}X^{0}+X^{2} & X^{1}+X^{3}\\
X^{1}-X^{3} & X^{2}-X^{0}
\end{pmatrix}.\label{eq:-31}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In this expression, the Einstein summation convention (according to which
 indices are raised and lowered using the Kleinian metric 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

) is temporarily suspended, and ordinary summation is employed instead.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{X}$
\end_inset

 satisfies two important properties:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underline{X}^{*}=\underline{X},\,\,\,\det\underline{X}=\left\langle X,X\right\rangle .\label{eq:-9}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first condition imposes a reality constraint, while the second relates
 the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{X}$
\end_inset

 to the Kleinian inner product of the four-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a transformation of the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underline{X}\mapsto U\underline{X}\widetilde{U}^{-1},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

to preserve the conditions given by Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-9"

\end_inset

), it is both necessary and sufficient that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}$
\end_inset

 take the forms:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=\exp\left(\sum_{i=1}^{3}\lambda_{i}\boldsymbol{\sigma}^{i}\right),\,\,\,\widetilde{U}=\exp\left(\sum_{i=1}^{3}\widetilde{\lambda}_{i}\boldsymbol{\sigma}^{i}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i},\widetilde{\lambda}_{i}\in\mathbf{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This construction realises the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2,2\right)$
\end_inset

 representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $SL\left(2,\mathbf{R}\right)\times\widetilde{SL\left(2,\mathbf{R}\right)}$
\end_inset

 within the vector representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(2,2\right)$
\end_inset

, as anticipated by the well-known isomorphism:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Spin\left(2,2\right)\simeq SL\left(2,\mathbf{R}\right)\times\widetilde{SL\left(2,\mathbf{R}\right)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus, the mapping defined by Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-31"

\end_inset

) allows the conversion between vector and spinor indices in Kleinian signature,
 as we claimed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Standard Null-vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To facilitate the parametrisation of the celestial sphere at null infinity,
 we introduce the pair of two-component spinors 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\eta}_{\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 These spinors are defined in terms of the angular coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta},\zeta\in\mathbf{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

, arising from the stereographic projection of the celestial sphere onto
 the complex plane, and are given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta^{A}\coloneqq\begin{pmatrix}\zeta\\
1
\end{pmatrix},\,\,\,\bar{\eta}_{\dot{A}}\coloneqq\begin{pmatrix}1 & -\bar{\zeta}\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\emph on
standard null four-vector
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\mu}=q^{\mu}(\zeta,\bar{\zeta})$
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q^{\mu}(\zeta,\bar{\zeta})\coloneqq\eta^{A}(\boldsymbol{\sigma}^{\mu})_{A\dot{A}}\bar{\eta}^{\dot{A}}=\left(\zeta\bar{\zeta}-1,\zeta+\bar{\zeta},1+\zeta\bar{\zeta},\zeta-\bar{\zeta}\right).\label{eq:-35}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Celestial Wavefunctions and the Leaf Amplitude Representation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Celestial-Wavefunctions-and"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The leaf representation of celestial amplitudes, introduced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "melton2023celestial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, arises from the consideration of the following integral over spacetime:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}\left(\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right)\coloneqq\int_{\mathbf{R}^{\left(2,2\right)}}d^{4}X\,\,\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(X\big|\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right).\label{eq:-32}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\Delta}\left(X\big|\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes the 
\emph on
celestial conformal primary wavefunction
\emph default
 for massless scalars with conformal weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{\Delta}\left(X\big|\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right)\coloneqq\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)}{\left(i\varepsilon+\langle\pi_{i}\big|X\big|\bar{\pi}_{i}]\right)^{\Delta}},\,\,\,\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)\coloneqq i^{-\Delta}\Gamma\left(\Delta\right).\label{eq:-3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spacetime integral in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-32"

\end_inset

) contains the key features of the leaf representation, which we subsequently
 employ to reduce from twistor to minitwistor variables.
 Thus, we briefly review its computation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the null cone 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 in 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{\left(2,2\right)}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
has zero measure, the spacetime integral can be decomposed as the sum of
 contributions from the time-like and space-like wedges:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}=\int_{\mathbf{W}^{-}}d^{4}X\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(X\big|\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right)+\int_{\mathbf{W}^{+}}d^{4}X\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(X\big|\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Employing the decomposition of the measures for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{-}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}^{+}$
\end_inset

, given (respectively) by Eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-33"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-34"

\end_inset

), the above expression can be reformulated as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}=\int_{\left(0,\infty\right)}d\tau\,\tau^{3}\int_{\mathbf{H}_{3}}d^{3}x\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(\tau x^{\mu}\big|\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right)+\int_{\left(0,\infty\right)}d\tau\,\tau^{3}\int_{\mathbf{H}_{3}^{+}}d^{3}x\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(\tau y^{\mu}\big|\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important property of these integrals follows from the parametrisation
 of the null four-vector introduced in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-35"

\end_inset

).
 In fact, it can be shown that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\mathbf{H}_{3}^{+}}d^{3}x\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(\tau y^{\mu}\big|\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right)=\int_{\mathbf{H}_{3}}d^{3}x\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(\tau x^{\mu}\big|\pi_{i},-\bar{\pi}_{i}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result allows one to replace the integration over the unit hyperboloid
 in the space-like wedge, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{+}^{3}$
\end_inset

, with an integration over the standard Kleinian hyperboloid in the time-like
 wedge, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

, provided the substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\pi}_{i\dot{A}}\mapsto-\bar{\pi}_{i\dot{A}}$
\end_inset

 is made for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Accordingly, the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}=\int_{\left(0,\infty\right)}d\tau\,\tau^{3}\int_{\mathbf{H}_{3}}d^{3}x\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(\tau x^{\mu}\big|\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right)+(\bar{\pi}_{i\dot{A}}\rightarrow-\bar{\pi}_{i\dot{A}}),\label{eq:-36}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bar{\pi}_{i\dot{A}}\rightarrow-\bar{\pi}_{i\dot{A}})$
\end_inset

 signifies the repetition of the first term with the indicated substitution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Factorising the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-dependence, we rewrite the integrand as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\prod_{i=1}^{n}\phi_{2h_{i}}\left(\tau x^{\mu}\big|\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right)=\tau^{-2\sum_{i=1}^{n}h_{i}}\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(2h_{i}\right)}{\left(i\varepsilon'+\langle\pi_{i}\big|x\big|\bar{\pi}_{i}]\right)^{2h_{i}}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon'$
\end_inset

 is a redefined infinitesimal regulator.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting this expression into Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-36"

\end_inset

), we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}=\int_{\left(0,\infty\right)}d\tau\,\tau^{3-2\sum_{i=1}^{n}h_{i}}\int_{\mathbf{H}_{3}}d^{3}x\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(2h_{i}\right)}{\left(i\varepsilon'+\langle\pi_{i}\big|x\big|\bar{\pi}_{i}]\right)^{2h_{i}}}+(\bar{\pi}_{i\dot{A}}\rightarrow-\bar{\pi}_{i\dot{A}}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, using the generalised Dirac delta function, analytically continued
 to the complex domain as explained in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "donnay2020asymptotic"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we express this integral as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}=2\pi\delta\left(\beta\right)\int_{\mathbf{H}_{3}}d^{3}x\,\prod_{i=1}^{n}G_{2h_{i}}\left(x\big|\pi_{i},\bar{\pi}_{i}\right)+(\bar{\pi}_{i\dot{A}}\rightarrow-\bar{\pi}_{i\dot{A}}),\label{eq:-4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\coloneqq4-2\sum_{i=1}^{n}h_{i},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 is the bulk-to-boundary Green's function
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 may be obtained by the analytic continuation of the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $AdS_{3}$
\end_inset

 propagator, as studied by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "costa2014spinning"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and reviewed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "penedones2017tasi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

 may also be derived by an analogous procedure starting from the 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{3}^{+}$
\end_inset

-WZNW conformal primaries, discussed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "teschner1999mini"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, employing the techniques developed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gelfandgeneralized"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for the covariant Laplacian on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{3}$
\end_inset

, given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{\Delta}\left(x\big|\pi,\bar{\pi}\right)\coloneqq\frac{\mathcal{C}\left(\Delta\right)}{\left(i\varepsilon+\langle\pi\big|x\big|\bar{\pi}]\right)^{\Delta}}.\label{eq:-11}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset bibtex
LatexCommand bibtex
btprint "btPrintCited"
bibfiles "CCFT2"
options "../TTCFT/revtex-tds/bibtex/bst/revtex/aipnum4-2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

